WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.720 --> 00:00:04.640
Ladies and gentlemen, our program is about to begin.

2
00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:20.720
Good afternoon.

3
00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:25.500
My name is Max Diehn. I'm a professor at Stanford University in the

4
00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:29.340
Stanford Cancer Institute, and it's my distinct honor to

5
00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:33.100
serve as chair for this afternoon's Discovery Science

6
00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:36.680
Plenary titled "The Next Frontier in Minimal Residual Disease:

7
00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:37.880
Solid Tumors."

8
00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:41.140
Here are my disclosures.

9
00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:47.640
The topic of this session will be minimal residual disease.

10
00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:52.050
Minimal residual disease refers to low levels of tumor burden remaining

11
00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:54.150
after treatment in cancer patients.

12
00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:59.449
Now, MRD has been used to personalize treatment in hematologic

13
00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:03.190
malignancies for decades and has been very effective there to both escalate and

14
00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:04.360
deescalate therapy.

15
00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:09.280
However, until recently, there have not been sufficient advances

16
00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:12.440
to allow similar strategies to be applied in patients with solid tumors.

17
00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:17.260
However, over the last few years, MRD in solid tumors has become

18
00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:21.100
a growing area of interest due to advances both in understanding of biology

19
00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:25.080
of MRD, as well as techniques to detect it in

20
00:01:25.140 --> 00:01:25.620
patients.

21
00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:31.080
Now, to frame this session, I want to make an important

22
00:01:31.100 --> 00:01:35.080
distinction between two types of MRD in solid tumors.

23
00:01:35.240 --> 00:01:39.100
It's important to recognize that there's really two different subsets of

24
00:01:39.280 --> 00:01:42.980
MRD we're talking about. The first is MRD after systemic

25
00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:46.960
therapy. This mainly occurs in patients with advanced disease who are

26
00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:49.840
treated with systemic therapy, have a deep response,

27
00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:54.500
and then have either no radiographic disease or still some

28
00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:58.360
small amounts of radiographic disease, both of which contain residual

29
00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:02.060
tumor cells. Now the biologic cause of this type of MRD is

30
00:02:02.070 --> 00:02:05.710
persister cells that are resistant to the prior line of therapy.

31
00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:10.500
Because of that, it's in a way more analogous to the MRD we see in hematologic

32
00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:14.160
malignancies, which of course are treated primarily with systemic therapies.

33
00:02:15.420 --> 00:02:19.400
And because these cells are resistant to the prior line of therapy, this type

34
00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:22.360
of MRD is relatively more challenging to treat.

35
00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:27.580
The second type of MRD is MRD that occurs after

36
00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:31.460
local therapy, and this is predominantly in patients with early-stage disease

37
00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.450
who have a visible primary tumor, in this example here in the lung, but

38
00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:39.360
also have micrometastatic deposits that are not recognized clinically.

39
00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:42.740
Those patients undergo surgery and appear cancer-free, but still have the

40
00:02:42.780 --> 00:02:46.760
micrometastatic disease, i.e., their minimal residual disease, that can then later

41
00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:50.660
give rise to recurrence. The biological cause of this type of

42
00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:54.620
MRD is the microscopic metastases, and this type of MRD

43
00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:58.410
may be easier to treat because these cancer cells generally have not experienced

44
00:02:58.560 --> 00:03:02.480
systemic therapy. So keep these two types of MRD in mind as we listen to

45
00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:05.820
the upcoming speakers. Now, as a

46
00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:10.370
Discovery Science Plenary, this session will span the spectrum from

47
00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:13.340
basic biology through translation to the clinic.

48
00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:18.340
And the first talk will be Dr. Hata focusing on evolution of drug

49
00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:21.920
resistance in non-small cell lung cancer. The second talk by Dr.

50
00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:23.040
Marine

51
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.540
focused on plasticity as a driver of MRD, particularly in melanomas.

52
00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:31.260
The third talk will be by Dr. Landau and will be a bridging talk.

53
00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:35.560
It will include some discussion of the biology of MRD, but

54
00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:39.180
also begin to talk about how we detect MRD in patients with

55
00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:40.440
early-stage

56
00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:44.170
disease who have MRD. And then, to finish it off, Dr.

57
00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:48.420
Ti will talk about advances in clinical trials and

58
00:03:48.580 --> 00:03:52.400
recent clinical results and how we are using MRD in the clinic to personalize

59
00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:53.680
treatment for patients.

60
00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:55.460
And with that,

61
00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:59.960
I will move on and introduce the

62
00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:03.100
first speaker. Our first speaker is Dr. Aaron Hata.

63
00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.720
He is an associate professor at Massachusetts General Hospital

64
00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:10.490
and Harvard Medical School, and his talk is titled "From

65
00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:13.780
Persistence to Relapse: Evolution of Drug Resistance in Lung Cancer."

66
00:04:14.420 --> 00:04:14.840
Dr. Hata.

67
00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:23.700
Good afternoon.

68
00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:33.380
Here are my disclosures. Of note in this presentation, I will discuss

69
00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:37.340
research performed as a sponsored research collaboration with Pfizer Oncology.

70
00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:43.640
Over the past two decades, the treatment of advanced non-small

71
00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:47.120
cell lung cancer has emerged as a success story of precision

72
00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:47.800
oncology.

73
00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:52.490
When a patient is diagnosed, we genotype their tumors to identify

74
00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:56.440
oncogenic mutations in driver genes that dictate

75
00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:58.620
which type of therapy the patient will receive.

76
00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:02.780
These include mutations in receptor tyrosine kinases such as

77
00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:06.400
EGFR, MET, and HER2, which lead to ligand-independent

78
00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:07.690
constitutive activation;

79
00:05:09.060 --> 00:05:12.780
gene fusions involving the kinase domains of receptor tyrosine

80
00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:16.580
kinases such as ALK, ROS1, and RET, leading to expression, constitutive

81
00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:20.720
dimerization, and activation; or mutations in downstream

82
00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.140
signaling mediators such as RAS or RAF.

83
00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:27.820
Currently, in the United States, there are over 25

84
00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:31.580
FDA-approved targeted therapies targeting nine different

85
00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:33.340
oncogenic drivers in lung cancer.

86
00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:39.120
These therapies are quite effective, inducing deep and durable

87
00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:42.980
regressions, leading to improved patient survival and quality of life.

88
00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:47.300
However, these therapies are not curative, and complete

89
00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:51.160
responses are rare. Inevitably, acquired drug resistance

90
00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:55.120
develops, and leading to disease relapse at sites of residual disease.

91
00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:59.760
I'd like to start today by telling you about a patient that we treated at our

92
00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:03.710
cancer center about 10 years ago. This patient was diagnosed with EGFR

93
00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:07.620
mutant lung cancer and was treated with the first-generation EGFR inhibitor,

94
00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:11.348
erlotinib.When the patient progressed, we biopsied the

95
00:06:11.368 --> 00:06:14.868
tumor and identified an EGFR T790M resistance mutation.

96
00:06:15.708 --> 00:06:19.248
The patient then went on a clinical trial of an investigational third-generation

97
00:06:19.288 --> 00:06:21.788
EGFR inhibitor that can overcome T790M.

98
00:06:22.928 --> 00:06:26.828
We began to track the mutations in the blood, and as the patient responded, we

99
00:06:26.848 --> 00:06:29.108
observed that the mutations became undetectable.

100
00:06:30.288 --> 00:06:33.928
Unfortunately, this was short-lived, and the mutations returned along with a new

101
00:06:33.948 --> 00:06:37.748
BRAF V600E mutation. This coincided with an

102
00:06:37.808 --> 00:06:41.688
isolated progression in a liver lesion, which was biopsied, confirming the

103
00:06:41.728 --> 00:06:42.648
BRAF mutation.

104
00:06:43.588 --> 00:06:46.168
The patient then underwent cryoablation of that lesion,

105
00:06:47.308 --> 00:06:51.268
after which point the BRAF mutation disappeared, but another EGFR resistance

106
00:06:51.348 --> 00:06:53.568
mutation, C797S, emerged.

107
00:06:54.548 --> 00:06:57.768
The patient came off the trial and was treated with subsequent lines of

108
00:06:57.788 --> 00:07:01.648
chemotherapy, during which point some of the EGFR mutations went up in the blood

109
00:07:01.728 --> 00:07:05.668
while others went down, highlighting different clonal responses to the

110
00:07:05.688 --> 00:07:06.068
therapy.

111
00:07:07.088 --> 00:07:10.818
Finally, the patient progressed again, and a biopsy revealed that the tumor had

112
00:07:10.848 --> 00:07:14.118
transformed from non-small cell lung cancer to small cell lung cancer,

113
00:07:14.578 --> 00:07:17.688
another known mechanism of resistance to EGFR TKIs.

114
00:07:18.768 --> 00:07:22.568
This patient highlights the evolutionary nature of clinical acquired drug

115
00:07:22.628 --> 00:07:26.508
resistance, which is continually shaped by the

116
00:07:26.548 --> 00:07:30.068
shifting landscapes, the fitness landscapes that are created by the different

117
00:07:30.078 --> 00:07:32.628
therapies that we treat our patients with.

118
00:07:34.628 --> 00:07:38.468
My lab has become interested in understanding the mechanisms that

119
00:07:38.508 --> 00:07:39.598
govern tumor evolution.

120
00:07:40.408 --> 00:07:44.208
But to describe the way we think about tumor evolution, I need to go back to

121
00:07:44.268 --> 00:07:48.148
this influential paper published in 2010 by Jeff Settleman and colleagues.

122
00:07:49.068 --> 00:07:52.608
They showed that when cancer cell lines were treated with targeted therapies,

123
00:07:53.068 --> 00:07:56.288
a small population of cancer cells could survive therapy.

124
00:07:56.878 --> 00:08:00.708
They termed these cells drug-tolerant persisters, borrowing terminology

125
00:08:00.748 --> 00:08:03.988
from bacterial persisters that had been described in the 1940s.

126
00:08:04.808 --> 00:08:08.668
Bacterial persisters are subpopulations of bacteria that can survive an

127
00:08:08.708 --> 00:08:12.168
environmental stress, such as an antibiotic, and then

128
00:08:12.228 --> 00:08:16.048
repopulate when the antibiotic or the environmental stress is removed.

129
00:08:16.868 --> 00:08:20.328
Importantly, bacterial persisters are distinct from resistant

130
00:08:20.368 --> 00:08:23.418
bacteria in that they do not harbor fixed genetic resistance.

131
00:08:24.708 --> 00:08:28.368
Similarly, drug-tolerant persisters do not harbor fixed

132
00:08:28.748 --> 00:08:32.737
resistance but are characterized by epigenetic plasticity creating

133
00:08:32.808 --> 00:08:36.728
drug tolerance that is reversible with withdrawal of the therapy.

134
00:08:39.308 --> 00:08:43.249
Subsequently, in our work, we observed that EGFR mutant cell lines

135
00:08:43.288 --> 00:08:45.368
consistently evolve T790M.

136
00:08:46.448 --> 00:08:49.228
However, they did so with varying frequencies.

137
00:08:49.808 --> 00:08:53.628
In some cases, resistance emerged very quickly after only a

138
00:08:53.688 --> 00:08:56.808
few weeks, while in other cases, it took months or years.

139
00:08:57.948 --> 00:09:01.728
We hypothesized that perhaps the late-evolving clones might

140
00:09:01.788 --> 00:09:04.988
represent evolution of resistance from drug-tolerant persisters.

141
00:09:06.028 --> 00:09:09.748
In subsequent work, we went on to demonstrate that yes, indeed, early

142
00:09:09.808 --> 00:09:10.768
resistant clones

143
00:09:11.848 --> 00:09:15.578
evolved from rare preexisting T790M clones that were present in the

144
00:09:15.608 --> 00:09:19.188
population, whereas late resistance evolved from

145
00:09:19.208 --> 00:09:22.818
persister cells that went on to de novo acquire resistance

146
00:09:22.868 --> 00:09:26.848
mutations such as EGFR T790M or other mechanisms

147
00:09:26.868 --> 00:09:29.748
of genomic resistance during the course of therapy.

148
00:09:31.808 --> 00:09:35.158
These results demonstrated that at least in preclinical models,

149
00:09:35.988 --> 00:09:39.558
clinical-acquired resistance could result from a multi-step evolutionary

150
00:09:39.628 --> 00:09:43.388
process in which persister cells subsequently evolve genomic

151
00:09:43.428 --> 00:09:44.708
mechanisms of resistance.

152
00:09:45.648 --> 00:09:48.628
But what was challenging was to know whether or not this happened in the clinic,

153
00:09:49.288 --> 00:09:52.758
owing to the limited nature of tumor sampling that we can achieve with

154
00:09:52.788 --> 00:09:56.748
clinical tumor biopsies. However, given the stress

155
00:09:56.848 --> 00:09:57.568
that these cells

156
00:09:58.408 --> 00:10:02.028
undergo as they're in the persister state, we hypothesized that

157
00:10:02.068 --> 00:10:05.988
perhaps there might be hallmarks or signatures of the stress that would be

158
00:10:06.048 --> 00:10:09.588
reflected in the resistant tumors that might tell us which evolutionary

159
00:10:09.628 --> 00:10:11.708
trajectory the tumor had evolved through.

160
00:10:13.108 --> 00:10:16.968
To investigate this, we teamed up with Mike Lawrence at MGH to examine

161
00:10:16.978 --> 00:10:20.548
the genomes of clones that had evolved resistance through the

162
00:10:20.568 --> 00:10:24.457
persister trajectory and compared them to clones that have evolved from

163
00:10:24.488 --> 00:10:28.408
preexisting T790M cells that effectively had never

164
00:10:28.448 --> 00:10:29.548
been suppressed by drug.

165
00:10:31.078 --> 00:10:34.118
We observed that cells evolving through the persister state

166
00:10:34.808 --> 00:10:38.668
harbored a much higher tumor mutation burden, and specifically an increase

167
00:10:38.728 --> 00:10:40.548
in APOBEC signature mutations.

168
00:10:42.828 --> 00:10:46.508
APOBEC enzymes are a family of cytidine deaminases that catalyze the

169
00:10:46.528 --> 00:10:50.118
deamination of cytosine to uracil in single-stranded DNA and

170
00:10:50.248 --> 00:10:50.628
RNA.

171
00:10:51.988 --> 00:10:55.568
APOBECs have come to be known as a major source of mutagenesis in

172
00:10:55.648 --> 00:10:59.428
cancers, giving rise to C to T and C to G

173
00:10:59.508 --> 00:11:03.288
mutations in TPC motifs comprising Sanger signatures

174
00:11:03.628 --> 00:11:05.248
SBS2 and 13.

175
00:11:07.508 --> 00:11:11.088
APOBEC mutational signatures are enriched in virally mediated

176
00:11:11.168 --> 00:11:14.638
cancers such as HPV-associated head and neck cancer and cervical cancer,

177
00:11:15.248 --> 00:11:19.188
but they also occur in non-virally mediated cancers such as subsets

178
00:11:19.228 --> 00:11:21.028
of lung cancer and breast cancer.

179
00:11:22.648 --> 00:11:26.348
We surveyed the 11 APOBEC family members in a

180
00:11:26.408 --> 00:11:29.848
panel of EGFR and ALK lung cancer cell lines treated with targeted

181
00:11:29.888 --> 00:11:30.488
therapies.

182
00:11:31.728 --> 00:11:34.928
We observed heterogeneous expression levels of the different APOBECs, but

183
00:11:34.968 --> 00:11:38.808
consistently, we saw that APOBEC3A was upregulated after

184
00:11:38.888 --> 00:11:42.048
drug treatment and stayed elevated in persister cells.

185
00:11:43.488 --> 00:11:47.308
To understand whether this led to increased mutagenesis in these cells, we

186
00:11:47.408 --> 00:11:51.248
took advantage of the fact that APOBEC3A preferentially edits TPC

187
00:11:51.268 --> 00:11:53.968
motifs within structurally conserved hairpin loops.

188
00:11:55.048 --> 00:11:55.868
In particular,

189
00:11:56.688 --> 00:12:00.608
an mRNA hotspot in the DDOSD transcript provides

190
00:12:00.668 --> 00:12:04.618
a reliable way of assessing APOBEC editing in

191
00:12:04.648 --> 00:12:08.248
the lab. We observed, consistent with the

192
00:12:08.308 --> 00:12:11.898
increase in APOBEC3 expression, that RNA editing at this

193
00:12:11.908 --> 00:12:15.728
DDOSC hotspot increased in EGFR and ALK mutant lung

194
00:12:15.768 --> 00:12:17.428
cancer cell lines treated with targeted

195
00:12:17.438 --> 00:12:20.678
therapy.We subsequently have

196
00:12:20.778 --> 00:12:24.318
corroborated these findings by developing a live cell editing

197
00:12:24.398 --> 00:12:27.918
reporter that can read out APOBEC editing in living intact

198
00:12:27.998 --> 00:12:31.978
cells. In this reporter, we engineered APOBEC

199
00:12:31.998 --> 00:12:35.928
substrate hairpin into a hiBIT sequence, which disrupts complementation

200
00:12:35.958 --> 00:12:39.478
between hiBIT and largeBIT. Upon APOBEC3A editing,

201
00:12:40.198 --> 00:12:44.178
the hiBIT is converted into a form that can complement

202
00:12:44.218 --> 00:12:46.338
with largeBIT, generating a luminescent signal.

203
00:12:47.658 --> 00:12:51.418
Using this reporter, we observed that drug-induced APOBEC

204
00:12:51.478 --> 00:12:55.418
editing occurred within one to two days after treatment, and we were also

205
00:12:55.518 --> 00:12:58.978
able to quantify APOBEC in living cells

206
00:13:00.338 --> 00:13:04.198
representing different targeted therapy contexts and different APOBEC editing

207
00:13:04.258 --> 00:13:04.718
levels.

208
00:13:06.498 --> 00:13:10.178
So what are the consequences of APOBEC editing in persister cells?

209
00:13:11.078 --> 00:13:14.698
Persister cells bear hallmarks of DNA damage, shown here by

210
00:13:14.878 --> 00:13:16.538
increased gamma H2AX staining.

211
00:13:17.658 --> 00:13:19.048
In addition, persister cells

212
00:13:20.378 --> 00:13:24.068
exhibit increased double-strand DNA breaks, shown here by

213
00:13:24.178 --> 00:13:24.937
comet assay.

214
00:13:25.918 --> 00:13:29.578
When we knock down APOBEC3A in these cells, we can completely reverse the

215
00:13:29.638 --> 00:13:31.358
increase in double-strand DNA breaks.

216
00:13:33.038 --> 00:13:36.548
If we knock down APOBEC3B, we can also partially reverse this

217
00:13:36.578 --> 00:13:37.218
phenotype.

218
00:13:38.678 --> 00:13:42.598
To understand what the consequences of this induced genomic damage are

219
00:13:42.718 --> 00:13:46.518
in the context of residual disease, we generated xenograft tumors from

220
00:13:46.558 --> 00:13:50.318
knockdown cells or control cells, treated the mice to generate

221
00:13:50.358 --> 00:13:53.918
residual disease, and then sequenced individual persister clones.

222
00:13:55.118 --> 00:13:58.218
As expected, we noted increased APOBEC mutations and structural

223
00:13:58.298 --> 00:14:01.918
variations in the control cells. However, in

224
00:14:01.938 --> 00:14:05.398
APOBEC knockout cells, APOBEC mutations were

225
00:14:05.438 --> 00:14:09.368
eliminated, as well as structural variations, demonstrating that therapy-induced

226
00:14:09.458 --> 00:14:13.358
APOBEC mutagenesis can generate genomic instability in residual disease.

227
00:14:14.758 --> 00:14:18.338
Finally, we examined whether or not APOBEC mutagenesis impacted the

228
00:14:18.378 --> 00:14:19.798
evolution of drug resistance.

229
00:14:20.758 --> 00:14:24.438
In control cells, we see cells initially respond and then

230
00:14:24.518 --> 00:14:27.258
slowly become resistant as the persister clones grow out.

231
00:14:28.158 --> 00:14:32.078
However, in APOBEC3A knockdown cells, this persister outgrowth

232
00:14:32.178 --> 00:14:35.247
is largely abolished, suggesting that APOBEC3A-induced

233
00:14:35.258 --> 00:14:38.558
mutagenesis is contributing to the evolution of drug resistance.

234
00:14:40.418 --> 00:14:44.378
Finally, we examined whether patients that had progressed on targeted therapies

235
00:14:44.438 --> 00:14:47.818
exhibit evidence of APOBEC mutations in their tumors.

236
00:14:47.858 --> 00:14:51.358
In this cohort of patients, we observed increased APOBEC mutational

237
00:14:51.458 --> 00:14:54.498
signatures in most treated resistant tumors.

238
00:14:55.658 --> 00:14:59.338
And in most cases, these APOBEC mutations were not present before therapy.

239
00:15:00.458 --> 00:15:03.158
I'd like to highlight one exemplary patient.

240
00:15:03.698 --> 00:15:06.747
This was an ALK lung cancer patient that was treated with first, second, and

241
00:15:06.838 --> 00:15:09.958
third-generation ALK inhibitors over the course of many years.

242
00:15:11.058 --> 00:15:14.848
After progression on the first-generation inhibitor crizotinib, the patient was

243
00:15:14.878 --> 00:15:17.858
observed to have an E1210K ALK resistance mutation.

244
00:15:19.198 --> 00:15:22.478
When the patient was treated with brigatinib, they initially responded but then

245
00:15:22.518 --> 00:15:26.298
experienced a series of isolated sites of disease progression which were

246
00:15:26.318 --> 00:15:27.218
surgically resected.

247
00:15:28.038 --> 00:15:31.838
In each of these, we observed the E1210K resistance mutation along

248
00:15:31.898 --> 00:15:35.218
with another second ALK mutation in cis.

249
00:15:36.358 --> 00:15:39.918
Finally, after progression on the third-generation inhibitor lorlatinib, we

250
00:15:39.958 --> 00:15:43.878
observed the first two mutations with a third mutation.

251
00:15:44.578 --> 00:15:48.378
In addition to these mutations, we observed an increased mutational burden in

252
00:15:48.418 --> 00:15:52.358
each tumor during therapy, which was driven almost exclusively by an increase in

253
00:15:52.398 --> 00:15:53.558
APOBEC mutagenesis.

254
00:15:55.518 --> 00:15:58.518
We also noted that each individual resistance

255
00:15:58.558 --> 00:16:02.108
mutation occurred in a characteristic APOBEC signature

256
00:16:02.178 --> 00:16:04.948
motif in TPC motifs,

257
00:16:05.678 --> 00:16:09.558
indicating that APOBEC was generating the resistance mutations that

258
00:16:09.598 --> 00:16:11.778
caused tumor evolution in this patient.

259
00:16:13.858 --> 00:16:17.158
These results nominate APOBEC3A as a driver of

260
00:16:17.958 --> 00:16:21.938
persister evolution in lung cancers treated with targeted therapies and

261
00:16:22.018 --> 00:16:25.798
also suggest that in some contexts, APOBEC3A may also generate the

262
00:16:25.838 --> 00:16:28.298
resistance mutations that drive disease relapse.

263
00:16:30.518 --> 00:16:34.248
Our work is supported by similar work by the Bivona and

264
00:16:34.338 --> 00:16:38.217
Swanton groups that suggests that APOBEC3B can also have a role

265
00:16:38.258 --> 00:16:40.058
in targeted therapy drug resistance.

266
00:16:41.458 --> 00:16:45.198
And preceding our work, the idea of adaptive mutability was

267
00:16:45.238 --> 00:16:49.158
proposed by the Bardelli group based on their discovery that in colorectal

268
00:16:49.218 --> 00:16:52.408
cancers treated with EGFR and BRAF-directed therapies,

269
00:16:53.358 --> 00:16:56.908
mismatch repair is downregulated and error polymerases are

270
00:16:56.958 --> 00:17:00.208
upregulated, leading to increased DNA damage and mutability.

271
00:17:01.398 --> 00:17:04.679
Collectively, these studies suggest that therapy-induced genomic

272
00:17:04.719 --> 00:17:08.318
instability and increased mutagenesis may be a common

273
00:17:08.358 --> 00:17:12.098
mechanism that shapes tumor evolution during therapy in multiple

274
00:17:12.238 --> 00:17:13.858
different therapeutic contexts.

275
00:17:16.479 --> 00:17:19.278
For the second half of the talk, I'd like to switch gears and talk about

276
00:17:19.358 --> 00:17:20.699
unpublished work

277
00:17:21.959 --> 00:17:25.798
ongoing in our lab looking at residual disease in ALK-positive lung

278
00:17:25.838 --> 00:17:29.498
cancer. This project is led by an outstanding postdoc, Toshio

279
00:17:29.518 --> 00:17:30.018
Fujino,

280
00:17:30.858 --> 00:17:34.658
and started as a collaboration with Pfizer Oncology led by Darlin

281
00:17:34.718 --> 00:17:37.098
Mannucci, a computational biologist.

282
00:17:38.258 --> 00:17:42.238
Subsequently, this work has expanded and is now supported through a breakthrough

283
00:17:42.278 --> 00:17:46.118
cancer project, namely the Power to Cure ALK-Positive Lung Cancer

284
00:17:46.298 --> 00:17:46.838
Team Lab.

285
00:17:49.098 --> 00:17:52.918
So ALK-positive lung cancer or patients with ALK-positive lung cancer have

286
00:17:52.938 --> 00:17:56.338
experienced a rather dramatic improvement in

287
00:17:56.378 --> 00:18:00.338
prognosis with the development of successive generations of

288
00:18:00.398 --> 00:18:01.558
ALK-targeted therapies.

289
00:18:02.898 --> 00:18:06.498
This is the progression-free survival data from the Phase III CROWN trial,

290
00:18:07.418 --> 00:18:10.138
which tested the third-generation lorlatinib versus the

291
00:18:10.218 --> 00:18:13.778
first-generation crizotinib in the first-line

292
00:18:13.858 --> 00:18:14.258
setting.

293
00:18:15.318 --> 00:18:18.978
And as you can appreciate, lorlatinib demonstrated impressive efficacy.

294
00:18:19.598 --> 00:18:23.438
And at the last data cutoff with over six years of follow-up, the

295
00:18:23.478 --> 00:18:25.498
median progression was not yet

296
00:18:26.418 --> 00:18:30.008
achieved.Given this long duration of

297
00:18:30.048 --> 00:18:33.468
response, lorlatinib resistance provides a biologically

298
00:18:33.568 --> 00:18:36.268
compelling setting to study residual disease.

299
00:18:36.808 --> 00:18:40.748
However, it also poses challenges in terms of sampling

300
00:18:40.788 --> 00:18:44.768
tumors when deep responses are achieved by patients and the

301
00:18:44.788 --> 00:18:46.228
sites of disease are quite small.

302
00:18:47.728 --> 00:18:51.448
So to study residual disease in lorlatinib-treated ALK lung cancer,

303
00:18:52.188 --> 00:18:53.618
we turn to PDX models.

304
00:18:54.468 --> 00:18:57.858
Our cohort represented PDX models generated from

305
00:18:58.788 --> 00:19:02.148
treatment-naive tumors, which model first-line lorlatinib use,

306
00:19:02.848 --> 00:19:06.588
as well as models generated from patients who had experienced acquired

307
00:19:06.648 --> 00:19:10.068
resistance to early-generation ALK inhibitors with on-target

308
00:19:10.108 --> 00:19:12.448
resistance and remain sensitive to lorlatinib.

309
00:19:13.588 --> 00:19:17.108
These models can model residual disease in the second-line

310
00:19:17.128 --> 00:19:18.068
lorlatinib setting.

311
00:19:19.068 --> 00:19:22.968
We treated PDX tumor-bearing mice and sampled tumors before

312
00:19:23.028 --> 00:19:26.628
treatment at the point of maximal response in residual disease,

313
00:19:27.228 --> 00:19:30.628
and for those models that became resistant at the time of disease relapse.

314
00:19:31.568 --> 00:19:35.388
As you can see, these models recapitulate a range of disease

315
00:19:35.468 --> 00:19:39.388
responses, some with rather shallow disease responses, others with

316
00:19:39.428 --> 00:19:43.378
deep regressions, and the duration to response and time to

317
00:19:43.408 --> 00:19:44.528
resistance was variable,

318
00:19:45.548 --> 00:19:47.808
representing heterogeneity that we see in our patients.

319
00:19:49.308 --> 00:19:53.028
Here is an example of a residual tumor in which small

320
00:19:53.088 --> 00:19:56.908
persister clusters are maintained within an expanded

321
00:19:56.928 --> 00:19:57.908
stromal compartment.

322
00:20:00.088 --> 00:20:03.768
To characterize persister evolution in this context, we performed single-cell

323
00:20:03.848 --> 00:20:06.988
sequencing on residual tumors in the first-line

324
00:20:07.028 --> 00:20:08.598
lorlatinib-resistant context.

325
00:20:09.868 --> 00:20:13.508
After data integration, we performed pseudo-time analysis and mapped the

326
00:20:13.528 --> 00:20:17.108
pseudo-time clusters on treatment time points to generate a

327
00:20:17.148 --> 00:20:20.188
putative resistance trajectory spanning from

328
00:20:20.198 --> 00:20:24.068
pre-treatment tumors through residual disease and to

329
00:20:25.068 --> 00:20:25.548
relapse.

330
00:20:26.628 --> 00:20:30.308
Of note, we identified two clusters shown here as cluster five and

331
00:20:30.328 --> 00:20:34.088
cluster seven, which represented transitional clusters that

332
00:20:34.168 --> 00:20:38.147
bridged the transition from untreated tumors to

333
00:20:38.168 --> 00:20:39.057
residual disease.

334
00:20:41.328 --> 00:20:44.568
First, we looked at markers of lung lineage states.

335
00:20:45.748 --> 00:20:49.688
This enabled us to map putative lineage trajectories on top

336
00:20:49.748 --> 00:20:53.548
of our pseudo-time trajectory, highlighting a high degree of

337
00:20:53.588 --> 00:20:57.328
lineage plasticity over this treatment context, starting with

338
00:20:57.388 --> 00:21:01.268
AT2-like cells that subsequently evolve into multiple

339
00:21:01.278 --> 00:21:03.168
lineage states.

340
00:21:04.088 --> 00:21:07.988
In addition, we identified intermediate states including cluster

341
00:21:08.028 --> 00:21:11.508
one, which expressed SLC4A11, which is a

342
00:21:11.568 --> 00:21:15.248
recently described marker of a high plasticity cell state in

343
00:21:15.508 --> 00:21:15.818
cancer,

344
00:21:17.068 --> 00:21:19.408
as well as bridging clusters such as cluster seven,

345
00:21:20.928 --> 00:21:24.628
which exhibited a high expression of keratin 17 and other basal

346
00:21:24.708 --> 00:21:28.187
cell-like markers such as keratin five and TP63.

347
00:21:29.708 --> 00:21:32.868
We also observed lineage-specific upregulation

348
00:21:33.828 --> 00:21:37.808
of markers such as ERBB2, which have been described to

349
00:21:37.828 --> 00:21:40.248
drive adaptive resistance in ALK-positive

350
00:21:41.088 --> 00:21:43.048
preclinical models of drug resistance.

351
00:21:44.908 --> 00:21:48.668
Given the location of cluster seven on the lineage

352
00:21:48.688 --> 00:21:52.188
trajectory, we focused on it. We also noticed that this cluster

353
00:21:52.228 --> 00:21:56.068
expressed high levels of CD44, a cancer stem cell

354
00:21:56.108 --> 00:21:57.608
marker supporting the

355
00:21:59.008 --> 00:22:02.228
potential lineage plasticity of this cluster.

356
00:22:03.328 --> 00:22:07.068
Additionally, we observed expression of integrins as well as

357
00:22:07.108 --> 00:22:09.308
genes associated with extracellular matrix.

358
00:22:10.308 --> 00:22:13.968
Particularly, we observed expression of components of

359
00:22:14.008 --> 00:22:17.768
laminin 322, which is the main extracellular matrix

360
00:22:17.868 --> 00:22:20.408
protein that interacts with integrin alpha 6 beta 4,

361
00:22:21.268 --> 00:22:24.848
as well as multiple components of the basement membrane component

362
00:22:25.008 --> 00:22:25.768
collagen IV.

363
00:22:27.028 --> 00:22:30.788
These results suggested that cluster seven might resemble cells that are

364
00:22:30.848 --> 00:22:33.118
interacting with the tumor microenvironment.

365
00:22:36.628 --> 00:22:40.488
In multiple recent studies, keratin 17-positive aberrant

366
00:22:40.508 --> 00:22:44.208
basal cells have been identified in non-cancer

367
00:22:44.668 --> 00:22:48.567
lung disease states such as idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, where

368
00:22:48.588 --> 00:22:52.288
they orchestrate a pathological lung epithelial repair

369
00:22:52.358 --> 00:22:52.898
response.

370
00:22:53.988 --> 00:22:57.168
In addition, aberrant basaloid cells and related

371
00:22:57.178 --> 00:23:00.748
damage-associated transitional progenitors have

372
00:23:00.768 --> 00:23:04.748
been identified in other inflammatory lung diseases such as severe

373
00:23:04.788 --> 00:23:05.648
COVID infection.

374
00:23:07.628 --> 00:23:10.668
These cells represent dysfunctional injury repair.

375
00:23:11.428 --> 00:23:15.088
So in the setting of normal lung injury, the repair process

376
00:23:15.128 --> 00:23:18.988
involves transdifferentiation from AT2 cells to AT1

377
00:23:19.008 --> 00:23:21.778
cells. However, in pathological states,

378
00:23:22.248 --> 00:23:25.728
this repair process becomes dysfunctional with the

379
00:23:25.768 --> 00:23:29.348
generation of intermediate injury states such as alveolar

380
00:23:29.428 --> 00:23:32.788
damage intermediates or damage-associated

381
00:23:34.248 --> 00:23:35.748
transitional progenitor cells.

382
00:23:36.808 --> 00:23:40.378
Interactions between macrophages in the microenvironment and

383
00:23:40.488 --> 00:23:44.168
fibroblasts and these damaged epithelial cells can generate a

384
00:23:44.188 --> 00:23:47.928
positive feed-forward cycle mediated by

385
00:23:47.968 --> 00:23:51.708
TGF-beta, TNF alpha, and the deposition of extracellular matrix

386
00:23:51.788 --> 00:23:55.528
proteins that enforces a keratin 17 positive aberrant

387
00:23:55.628 --> 00:23:58.858
basaloid state, which promotes further inflammation and

388
00:23:58.928 --> 00:23:59.648
fibrosis.

389
00:24:01.528 --> 00:24:05.128
We wondered whether the keratin 17 positive cells that we observed in residual

390
00:24:05.168 --> 00:24:08.988
tumors might similarly be interacting with the tumor microenvironment.

391
00:24:10.008 --> 00:24:13.528
Indeed, pathological analysis of residual tumors indicated that these

392
00:24:13.568 --> 00:24:17.508
cells lined the tumor stroma boundary, suggesting that they're promoted

393
00:24:17.548 --> 00:24:20.348
by interactions with the microenvironment.

394
00:24:21.788 --> 00:24:25.128
So we hypothesized that during lorlatinib treatment, persister

395
00:24:25.188 --> 00:24:28.688
evolution might promote the keratin 17 positive state by

396
00:24:28.728 --> 00:24:31.528
interactions between CAFs and other components of the

397
00:24:31.548 --> 00:24:35.476
microenvironment.To study this, we generated

398
00:24:35.486 --> 00:24:39.386
ex vivo co-culture models generated from patient-derived tumor cells and

399
00:24:39.416 --> 00:24:43.356
patient-derived cancer-associated fibroblast cells from ALK lung cancer

400
00:24:43.426 --> 00:24:47.416
patients. By culturing these cells in 3D, the organoid

401
00:24:47.426 --> 00:24:50.346
models are able to recapitulate the tumor stroma boundaries.

402
00:24:50.816 --> 00:24:54.636
And we observe that even in the absence of treatment, tumor cells that lined

403
00:24:54.796 --> 00:24:58.716
the interface with fibroblasts upregulated expression of

404
00:24:58.756 --> 00:24:59.796
keratin 17.

405
00:25:01.936 --> 00:25:05.776
Next, to study the transition into the keratin 17 positive state,

406
00:25:05.916 --> 00:25:09.716
we generated reporter cell lines in which the induction of

407
00:25:09.736 --> 00:25:13.676
keratin 17 leads to expression of GFP, allowing us to

408
00:25:13.716 --> 00:25:17.196
visualize the cell state transition.

409
00:25:17.216 --> 00:25:21.186
When cultured by themselves, tumor cells rarely expressed keratin 17 or

410
00:25:21.216 --> 00:25:24.456
the GFP reporter. However, when cultured with fibroblasts,

411
00:25:25.336 --> 00:25:28.896
we observed that tumor cells in close approximation with a fibroblast

412
00:25:28.976 --> 00:25:30.676
upregulated keratin 17.

413
00:25:32.076 --> 00:25:35.316
Furthermore, when we treated these co-cultures with lorlatinib,

414
00:25:35.736 --> 00:25:39.355
we were able to induce further differentiation into the

415
00:25:39.396 --> 00:25:41.316
keratin 17 positive cell state.

416
00:25:42.976 --> 00:25:46.336
Next, we examined different components of the tumor microenvironment,

417
00:25:46.696 --> 00:25:50.116
including laminin 322, implicated in our single-cell sequencing,

418
00:25:50.896 --> 00:25:54.836
as well as markers such as TNF alpha and TGF beta, which

419
00:25:54.876 --> 00:25:58.416
are expressed by our fibroblasts and have been shown to induce a keratin 17

420
00:25:58.456 --> 00:26:00.886
positive state in lung injury contexts.

421
00:26:02.536 --> 00:26:06.136
By themselves, these microenvironment components induce

422
00:26:06.176 --> 00:26:09.136
variable levels of keratin 17

423
00:26:09.156 --> 00:26:12.816
positivity, but when combined with lorlatinib, this was

424
00:26:12.856 --> 00:26:13.456
enhanced.

425
00:26:15.256 --> 00:26:19.056
When we compare the induction of keratin 17 positive cells

426
00:26:19.116 --> 00:26:20.056
across these

427
00:26:21.456 --> 00:26:25.316
conditions, we can define a continuum of

428
00:26:25.376 --> 00:26:26.486
inducing efficiency

429
00:26:27.316 --> 00:26:30.476
suggesting that different components of the microenvironment might collaborate

430
00:26:30.516 --> 00:26:34.256
together to promote the generation of keratin 17

431
00:26:34.336 --> 00:26:35.396
positive tumor cells.

432
00:26:37.316 --> 00:26:41.116
To confirm that our GFP reporter was faithfully recapitulating the

433
00:26:41.136 --> 00:26:44.776
keratin 17 positive cell state that we observed in residual tumors,

434
00:26:45.376 --> 00:26:47.416
we sorted GFP-high and GFP-low

435
00:26:48.896 --> 00:26:49.256
cells

436
00:26:50.116 --> 00:26:53.536
from these different states, and we examined expression of keratin

437
00:26:53.596 --> 00:26:57.276
17 as well as other basaloid markers such as keratin

438
00:26:57.356 --> 00:27:01.296
five and keratin 14, which we confirmed were also expressed

439
00:27:01.356 --> 00:27:02.656
in the GFP-high cells.

440
00:27:05.196 --> 00:27:09.096
Finally, we asked whether or not the keratin 17 basaloid state might

441
00:27:09.156 --> 00:27:10.656
have a role in drug resistance.

442
00:27:12.036 --> 00:27:15.876
When we treated cancer cells with lorlatinib in the presence of

443
00:27:15.936 --> 00:27:19.496
the microenvironment components, we observed decreased drug

444
00:27:19.576 --> 00:27:23.236
sensitivity and increased persistence, suggesting that the keratin

445
00:27:23.296 --> 00:27:26.376
17 state may reflect an increased drug-tolerant

446
00:27:26.556 --> 00:27:27.296
population.

447
00:27:29.116 --> 00:27:32.676
Taken together, these results suggest that tumor

448
00:27:33.516 --> 00:27:37.236
persister evolution in ALK-positive lung cancer residual disease

449
00:27:37.936 --> 00:27:41.526
may reflect the dysfunctional epithelial regeneration

450
00:27:41.676 --> 00:27:45.196
states seen in non-cancer lung injury contexts,

451
00:27:45.836 --> 00:27:49.356
whereby cues from the microenvironment may enhance

452
00:27:49.416 --> 00:27:52.356
formation of a keratin 17 basal-like

453
00:27:53.136 --> 00:27:56.796
state with decreased drug sensitivity and increased lineage

454
00:27:56.876 --> 00:27:57.496
plasticity.

455
00:27:58.416 --> 00:28:02.126
We speculate that these cells may further evolve resistant states that

456
00:28:02.176 --> 00:28:05.716
recapitulate additional lung lineage trajectories.

457
00:28:08.856 --> 00:28:09.756
Our work

458
00:28:10.576 --> 00:28:12.546
supports the notion that

459
00:28:13.696 --> 00:28:17.096
lineage plasticity inherent in epithelial regeneration

460
00:28:17.656 --> 00:28:19.996
may promote residual disease.

461
00:28:21.156 --> 00:28:24.576
In a landmark study from 2020 from the Bivona group,

462
00:28:25.076 --> 00:28:28.976
they profiled residual tumors in lung cancer patients treated

463
00:28:28.996 --> 00:28:30.116
with targeted therapies.

464
00:28:30.936 --> 00:28:31.056
They

465
00:28:32.056 --> 00:28:35.816
observed a signature of alveolar injury and repair in persisting

466
00:28:35.856 --> 00:28:37.846
cancer cells in this state.

467
00:28:39.216 --> 00:28:43.076
In earlier this year, work from the Tamela group using mouse models

468
00:28:43.156 --> 00:28:47.056
of KRAS mutant lung cancer identified a high plasticity cell

469
00:28:47.196 --> 00:28:49.976
state that promoted tumor evolution and therapy

470
00:28:49.996 --> 00:28:53.776
resistance. Interestingly, they noted that the

471
00:28:53.795 --> 00:28:57.036
high plasticity cell state resembled some of the

472
00:28:57.496 --> 00:29:01.236
epithelial damage intermediates seen in non-cancer lung injury

473
00:29:01.296 --> 00:29:01.696
states.

474
00:29:02.636 --> 00:29:06.516
They also showed that non-cancer injury states could

475
00:29:06.556 --> 00:29:08.596
regenerate high plasticity cells.

476
00:29:10.536 --> 00:29:13.896
Collectively, these data support the

477
00:29:13.956 --> 00:29:17.476
paradigm in which lineage plasticity, which is

478
00:29:17.516 --> 00:29:20.636
governed by the normal lung differentiation axis

479
00:29:21.436 --> 00:29:24.836
and is reflected in the dysfunctional cell states

480
00:29:24.936 --> 00:29:25.456
in

481
00:29:26.276 --> 00:29:30.136
diseases such as idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis that are driven

482
00:29:30.176 --> 00:29:31.036
by lung injury,

483
00:29:32.636 --> 00:29:36.096
may also promote but also constrain persister

484
00:29:36.196 --> 00:29:40.046
evolution in targeted therapy persistent disease, being

485
00:29:40.076 --> 00:29:43.126
influenced by cell intrinsic properties as well as

486
00:29:43.196 --> 00:29:44.556
microenvironmental cues.

487
00:29:46.996 --> 00:29:47.896
So to conclude,

488
00:29:48.736 --> 00:29:52.516
today I hope I've showed you that therapy-persistent cancer cells in residual

489
00:29:52.536 --> 00:29:56.476
disease can acquire drug-resistant mechanisms through multi-step evolution.

490
00:29:57.996 --> 00:30:01.936
Therapy-induced adaptive mutagenesis can accelerate evolution

491
00:30:01.956 --> 00:30:05.816
of persister cells and drive disease relapse.

492
00:30:07.056 --> 00:30:10.856
And lineage-constrained lung epithelial injury states may provide a useful

493
00:30:10.936 --> 00:30:14.126
paradigm for understanding and targeting the early stages of

494
00:30:14.236 --> 00:30:16.176
therapy-persistent residual disease.

495
00:30:18.016 --> 00:30:21.736
With that, I'd like to conclude by acknowledging the large team of people that

496
00:30:21.776 --> 00:30:24.935
contributed to this work, some of whom I mentioned along the way.

497
00:30:25.856 --> 00:30:29.836
And I'd like to also acknowledge our funders, without whom this work would not be

498
00:30:29.916 --> 00:30:30.356
possible.

499
00:30:31.676 --> 00:30:32.056
Thank you.

500
00:30:41.176 --> 00:30:42.156
Thank you, Dr. Hata.

501
00:30:43.396 --> 00:30:47.296
Our next speaker is Dr. Chris Marine.

502
00:30:48.156 --> 00:30:51.766
He is a professor at the VBI at the

503
00:30:51.776 --> 00:30:53.456
University of Leuven in Belgium.

504
00:30:54.276 --> 00:30:57.896
His talk is titled, "Therapeutic Strategies to Address Cancer Cell

505
00:30:57.916 --> 00:30:59.556
Heterogeneity and Plasticity."

506
00:31:11.496 --> 00:31:12.476
Cancer cell plasticity.

507
00:31:14.156 --> 00:31:18.105
So cancer cell plasticity has emerged recently,

508
00:31:18.556 --> 00:31:20.056
as you have heard,

509
00:31:21.116 --> 00:31:23.066
as a key driver of therapy resistance.

510
00:31:23.996 --> 00:31:27.776
And this is satisfying for us because our lab has been promoting this idea for the

511
00:31:27.816 --> 00:31:29.176
last 10 years or so.

512
00:31:30.196 --> 00:31:30.855
But today, I'll

513
00:31:31.836 --> 00:31:33.476
flip the script a bit and

514
00:31:34.416 --> 00:31:38.306
I will show you that cancer plasticity can actually be leveraged

515
00:31:38.376 --> 00:31:41.776
to our advantage in order to mitigate therapy

516
00:31:41.796 --> 00:31:42.376
resistance.

517
00:31:44.796 --> 00:31:45.236
In fact,

518
00:31:46.816 --> 00:31:47.976
the idea is that,

519
00:31:49.656 --> 00:31:53.496
I will try to discuss this today, that plasticity might actually

520
00:31:53.556 --> 00:31:57.076
be a solution rather than a problem that we have to cope with.

521
00:32:00.236 --> 00:32:02.316
So my lab focus and work on melanoma,

522
00:32:03.556 --> 00:32:05.176
and like many other cancer types,

523
00:32:06.096 --> 00:32:09.196
targeted therapy has become one standard of care treatment.

524
00:32:10.596 --> 00:32:14.376
In this context, BRAF mutant patient melanoma are

525
00:32:14.396 --> 00:32:16.976
exposed to a combination of BRAF and MEK inhibitors.

526
00:32:18.496 --> 00:32:19.656
This treatment

527
00:32:21.016 --> 00:32:24.316
leads to very dramatic antitumor responses in patients, but as you all

528
00:32:24.356 --> 00:32:27.256
know resistance always develop.

529
00:32:28.606 --> 00:32:31.696
And this is obviously because this treatment does not kill all tumor cells.

530
00:32:32.416 --> 00:32:34.076
And one of the interesting question is

531
00:32:35.136 --> 00:32:35.976
why is that?

532
00:32:36.936 --> 00:32:40.476
And so obviously, not all tumor cells are created equals.

533
00:32:41.056 --> 00:32:44.736
While some cells may be eliminated by the treatment, others may undergo cell

534
00:32:44.776 --> 00:32:48.336
cycle arrest or even worse, continue cycling in response to the

535
00:32:48.436 --> 00:32:48.876
treatment.

536
00:32:50.196 --> 00:32:53.836
And in fact, in the context of melanoma, this is unfortunately very common.

537
00:32:55.496 --> 00:32:59.176
Melanoma, as you may recall, is the tumor type with the highest mutation

538
00:32:59.236 --> 00:33:03.136
burden. So it actually is very common to detect

539
00:33:03.376 --> 00:33:05.156
before therapy is

540
00:33:06.276 --> 00:33:06.716
applied,

541
00:33:07.696 --> 00:33:11.356
numbers of cells that have already acquired genetic alterations

542
00:33:11.676 --> 00:33:13.576
that confer resistance to the treatment.

543
00:33:15.476 --> 00:33:18.836
Such as, for example, a mutation in the MEK1 gene or NRAS gene.

544
00:33:20.176 --> 00:33:23.816
And so when these tumors are exposed to the treatment, resistance

545
00:33:23.856 --> 00:33:27.356
rapidly emerge due to the selection of this preexisting

546
00:33:27.416 --> 00:33:27.996
subclone.

547
00:33:28.836 --> 00:33:32.676
So there is basically a clear genetic evidence in the context of melanoma

548
00:33:33.316 --> 00:33:36.815
of tumor evolution, and this occurs in about 50% of the cases.

549
00:33:40.136 --> 00:33:43.896
Now, besides genetic alterations, plasticity

550
00:33:43.966 --> 00:33:47.036
can be obviously a potential source of phenotypic diversity.

551
00:33:47.656 --> 00:33:51.596
But does it play an important role in melanoma, given that melanoma is the tumor

552
00:33:51.636 --> 00:33:53.296
type with the highest mutation burden?

553
00:33:55.636 --> 00:33:59.416
So to address these questions, we leveraged single-cell RNA sequencing, collected

554
00:33:59.596 --> 00:34:03.156
numbers of clinical samples, as well as lesions from different mouse models,

555
00:34:03.896 --> 00:34:07.536
and realized that indeed, melanoma cells are not all created equal.

556
00:34:08.616 --> 00:34:12.316
They exist in a lineage-specific continuum of cell

557
00:34:12.377 --> 00:34:12.816
states.

558
00:34:13.917 --> 00:34:16.996
Some cells, for example, turn on a melanocytic

559
00:34:17.457 --> 00:34:21.236
program or MEL program which is characterized by high expression

560
00:34:21.437 --> 00:34:25.377
of pigment-producing genes, such as those found in

561
00:34:25.397 --> 00:34:26.426
normal melanocytes,

562
00:34:27.576 --> 00:34:31.336
while other cells shift along a dedifferentiation trajectory and

563
00:34:31.417 --> 00:34:35.236
turn on a transitory or fetal embryonic neural

564
00:34:35.276 --> 00:34:38.116
crest-like or even mesenchymal-like state.

565
00:34:39.296 --> 00:34:42.917
When cells turn on the mesenchymal-like phenotype, these cells lose almost

566
00:34:42.957 --> 00:34:46.917
completely their melanocytic identity, and we therefore refer to

567
00:34:46.937 --> 00:34:48.496
this as dedifferentiation.

568
00:34:50.556 --> 00:34:54.377
The key observation is that this transcriptomic heterogeneity is

569
00:34:54.417 --> 00:34:56.536
not driven by the genetic makeup of the cells.

570
00:34:56.696 --> 00:35:00.176
For example, here we leveraged sequencing-based spatial

571
00:35:00.196 --> 00:35:03.035
transcriptomics to demonstrate that most

572
00:35:04.596 --> 00:35:07.456
metastatic melanoma lesions we looked at are

573
00:35:08.496 --> 00:35:12.176
genetically monoclonal, yet they exhibit

574
00:35:12.296 --> 00:35:13.656
transcriptomic heterogeneity.

575
00:35:15.336 --> 00:35:19.156
So these experiments, among others, led us to conclude that cell

576
00:35:19.216 --> 00:35:23.156
plasticity does contribute to phenotypic diversity, even in the context

577
00:35:23.196 --> 00:35:23.796
of melanoma.

578
00:35:25.256 --> 00:35:29.116
But does it contribute to therapy resistance, and in particular, to the

579
00:35:29.156 --> 00:35:30.016
drug tolerance?

580
00:35:31.436 --> 00:35:35.196
And to address this question, we generated PDX models from patients that

581
00:35:35.476 --> 00:35:37.056
responded well to the treatment.

582
00:35:38.336 --> 00:35:42.076
Treatment of these mice mirror what we see in

583
00:35:42.396 --> 00:35:46.216
patients, so meaning that tumors regress in these mice and eventually all

584
00:35:46.256 --> 00:35:47.836
recur on treatment.

585
00:35:49.276 --> 00:35:50.536
So to disentangle the

586
00:35:51.476 --> 00:35:54.816
contribution of the genetic versus non-genetic mechanism of tumor

587
00:35:54.876 --> 00:35:55.496
evolution

588
00:35:56.576 --> 00:35:58.036
in these models, we

589
00:35:58.896 --> 00:36:02.296
collected cells at different time point and apply GNT-seq,

590
00:36:02.976 --> 00:36:06.736
allowing us to sequence the genome and transcriptome of the same cells.

591
00:36:09.236 --> 00:36:13.076
What we've learned looking at the genome is that we didn't find any evidence of

592
00:36:13.296 --> 00:36:16.596
subclonal genetic evolution or selection at minimal residual

593
00:36:16.656 --> 00:36:19.896
disease. And when we look at the transcriptome, we

594
00:36:20.316 --> 00:36:24.116
notice that the dedifferentiated neural crest-like or the mesenchymal cells were

595
00:36:24.156 --> 00:36:24.276
the

596
00:36:25.096 --> 00:36:28.996
cells that were accumulated the most at MRD on treatment.

597
00:36:30.156 --> 00:36:33.866
And importantly, accumulation of these dedifferentiated cells was a consequence of

598
00:36:33.896 --> 00:36:37.636
two things. One, a passive selection of a

599
00:36:37.716 --> 00:36:40.996
rare preexisting subpopulation, but also in some

600
00:36:41.036 --> 00:36:44.816
case, due to adaptive reprogramming and

601
00:36:46.076 --> 00:36:49.196
induction of this program due to the therapy

602
00:36:49.236 --> 00:36:52.920
itselfIndicating that even in the context of melanoma,

603
00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:55.800
plasticity does contribute to the drug tolerance.

604
00:36:58.020 --> 00:37:01.860
So based on this data, we then design strategies that prevent

605
00:37:01.880 --> 00:37:05.860
emergence of these de-differentiated cells or that target these cells

606
00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:08.320
at MRD. For example, we use

607
00:37:09.260 --> 00:37:13.240
inhibitors of specific transcription factors or epigenetic modifiers,

608
00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:14.340
or to target

609
00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:19.120
the vulnerabilities of these persistent cells at MRD, we use, for example,

610
00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:23.260
focal adhesion kinase inhibitors or inhibitors of de novo lipid synthesis.

611
00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:28.740
Now, although all of these strategies delay time to progression

612
00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:32.800
significantly in PDX models, none of those strategies,

613
00:37:32.940 --> 00:37:35.620
even when combined, were actually curative.

614
00:37:37.560 --> 00:37:41.510
And the reason for this is that we realized that minimal residual disease in the

615
00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:44.500
context of melanoma is more complex than we initially thought.

616
00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:46.450
De-differentiation is only part of

617
00:37:47.400 --> 00:37:47.840
the story.

618
00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:52.840
In fact, we identify at least four different drug

619
00:37:52.880 --> 00:37:56.300
persistent cell phenotypes that could eventually

620
00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:58.260
co-emerge in one single MRD.

621
00:37:59.440 --> 00:38:03.220
For example, here on the left, we have a PDX-derived MRD that

622
00:38:03.260 --> 00:38:06.640
shows three different persistent phenotypes that occupy a

623
00:38:06.680 --> 00:38:09.700
geographically distinct region in this lesion.

624
00:38:10.640 --> 00:38:12.560
On the right, you have numbers of

625
00:38:14.180 --> 00:38:18.060
MRDs from clinical samples, and what you can see is that each MRD in

626
00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:22.040
melanoma is a complex ecosystem with very distinct cellular

627
00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:22.480
makeup.

628
00:38:27.880 --> 00:38:31.820
So our work uncover extreme genotypic heterogeneity and

629
00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:33.660
phenotypic diversity in melanoma.

630
00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:37.680
And not only we find that the cellular makeup of MRD is complex,

631
00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:39.540
heterogeneous, and patient-specific,

632
00:38:40.420 --> 00:38:44.120
we also find evidence that distinct genetic and non-genetic evolutionary

633
00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:47.940
mechanisms can be at play in different lesions from the same patient or

634
00:38:47.980 --> 00:38:49.760
worst, in a single individual

635
00:38:50.980 --> 00:38:51.320
lesion.

636
00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:56.600
So this data highlighted the challenges of personalized treatment in the

637
00:38:56.640 --> 00:38:58.280
context of melanoma. In fact,

638
00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:01.699
it's almost as if we need to develop

639
00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:06.140
lesion-specific therapy as opposed to personalized therapy.

640
00:39:06.860 --> 00:39:10.600
And so all this to say that what we think is that personalized

641
00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:13.900
therapy in melanoma should still be a long-term goal.

642
00:39:14.340 --> 00:39:18.060
The clinical implementation will be extremely challenging and therefore,

643
00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:20.740
not necessarily for tomorrow, unfortunately.

644
00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:25.940
So we reason that

645
00:39:26.880 --> 00:39:30.820
one way to approach this problem would be to move beyond personalized therapy.

646
00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:33.920
What if we could develop therapeutic

647
00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:38.870
regimens that are effective irrespective of the genetic background, the cellular

648
00:39:38.940 --> 00:39:42.700
makeup of the cells, and that can contend with cancer cell plasticity?

649
00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:47.000
This would obviously be fantastic, but is that

650
00:39:47.620 --> 00:39:48.220
realistic?

651
00:39:50.420 --> 00:39:52.280
Adrian De Blonder, a post-doc in the lab,

652
00:39:53.380 --> 00:39:56.460
decided to tackle this rather provocative

653
00:39:58.040 --> 00:39:58.900
approach question.

654
00:40:00.220 --> 00:40:03.960
And the first thing he did is to try to develop a new framework

655
00:40:04.340 --> 00:40:08.000
in which cancer cell plasticity and heterogeneity are no longer

656
00:40:08.040 --> 00:40:10.889
defined by complex multi-omics signatures.

657
00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:13.000
So

658
00:40:13.980 --> 00:40:17.400
basically, he was inspired by the definition of phenotype,

659
00:40:18.080 --> 00:40:21.960
which was first coined as the observable traits or appearance of an

660
00:40:22.020 --> 00:40:22.480
organism,

661
00:40:23.560 --> 00:40:26.360
and decided to look more carefully at our melanoma cells.

662
00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:31.770
And indeed, looking at melanoma cells under the microscope, we realized that

663
00:40:31.880 --> 00:40:35.800
cells that exhibit very distinct transcriptomic signatures look

664
00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:37.579
quite distinct morphologically.

665
00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:43.260
So we then teamed up with a company called DeepCell that developed a

666
00:40:43.300 --> 00:40:46.900
high-resolution live-cell imaging and deep learning platform

667
00:40:47.240 --> 00:40:50.860
that allows to classify cells according to morphometrics measurements.

668
00:40:52.520 --> 00:40:54.100
And we profiled more than 20 different

669
00:40:55.360 --> 00:40:59.220
melanoma cell lines spanning a wide range of genetic as

670
00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:00.740
well as transcriptomic profiles.

671
00:41:01.680 --> 00:41:03.280
And remarkably, we realized that

672
00:41:04.220 --> 00:41:07.419
melanoma cells that exhibit common transcriptomic features

673
00:41:07.859 --> 00:41:11.799
occupy discrete UMAP areas in these

674
00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:13.160
UMAP plots,

675
00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:17.900
indicating that morphometrics could be used as a way to

676
00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:19.960
decode melanoma cell state diversity.

677
00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:23.780
Adrian then

678
00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:28.680
did a numbers of trial and errors and developed a very simple FACS method that we

679
00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:32.640
call Origami, that measure only two different parameters, the

680
00:41:32.700 --> 00:41:34.640
cell surface area and the volume.

681
00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:39.140
To measure the cell surface area, Adrian used membrane, which is a

682
00:41:39.580 --> 00:41:43.280
dye that stains lipid to the cell surface, and as a proxy for cell

683
00:41:43.420 --> 00:41:45.860
volume, Adrian used forward scatter width.

684
00:41:47.240 --> 00:41:50.920
And with this very simple, scalable, and cost-efficient method, we now can

685
00:41:50.980 --> 00:41:54.420
capture the entire diversity of melanoma cell state.

686
00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:58.840
Here, for example, I've shown a dozen of melanoma cell lines that are

687
00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:02.580
representative of the four transcriptomic states, and you can see they are well

688
00:42:02.680 --> 00:42:06.060
separated onto this UMAP plot, onto this

689
00:42:06.440 --> 00:42:07.400
two-dimensional space.

690
00:42:08.900 --> 00:42:12.340
What's interesting about this approach is that you can basically define cell

691
00:42:12.460 --> 00:42:15.920
state in the absence of any omic measurements.

692
00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:19.120
Here we propose to define on this

693
00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:24.920
cell geometric framework to define cell state at the position or the

694
00:42:24.960 --> 00:42:27.460
coordinate of a cell into this SV space.

695
00:42:30.280 --> 00:42:33.740
We adapted this method, Origami, to able to monitor

696
00:42:34.040 --> 00:42:36.340
intratumor heterogeneity in clinical samples.

697
00:42:36.920 --> 00:42:39.560
We needed to add lineage depletion steps.

698
00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:42.720
So we basically depleted now all the

699
00:42:43.480 --> 00:42:47.460
immune cells as well as the fibroblast before proceeding to the SV

700
00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:51.400
measurement. The whole procedure take only 20 minutes, and as you can

701
00:42:51.440 --> 00:42:55.200
see, the SV readout is a very good proxy or basically a very good

702
00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:59.160
predictor of the tumor cell composition of these biopsies

703
00:42:59.600 --> 00:43:02.760
as defined by single-cell RNA sequencing on the same clinical

704
00:43:02.820 --> 00:43:06.628
sample.So the point I'd like to make is

705
00:43:06.668 --> 00:43:10.588
that there is great value at developing more and more sophisticated

706
00:43:11.408 --> 00:43:13.868
approaches to gain new biological insights.

707
00:43:14.268 --> 00:43:17.748
But impact can also be achieved by creating very simple and cheap alternatives,

708
00:43:17.908 --> 00:43:20.368
such as origami, which can be implemented

709
00:43:21.368 --> 00:43:23.007
very quickly into clinical routine.

710
00:43:25.588 --> 00:43:25.708
Now,

711
00:43:26.608 --> 00:43:29.668
this method can also be used to study adaptation to treatment.

712
00:43:30.208 --> 00:43:34.068
And for example, here, in response to the standard of care treatment, so BRAF/MEK

713
00:43:34.108 --> 00:43:38.048
inhibitors, you can see that cells can adapt, and

714
00:43:38.288 --> 00:43:41.248
the surviving cells can change their morphology in different ways.

715
00:43:41.948 --> 00:43:45.928
And this is very similar to what I told you earlier, meaning that in response

716
00:43:45.948 --> 00:43:49.518
to the particular treatment, melanoma cells can turn on

717
00:43:49.588 --> 00:43:51.427
different persistent phenotypes.

718
00:43:55.088 --> 00:43:55.208
Now,

719
00:43:56.328 --> 00:44:00.108
measuring cancer cell plasticity has always been rather challenging,

720
00:44:01.248 --> 00:44:03.448
and it was a bit unclear how to do that.

721
00:44:03.648 --> 00:44:07.148
So what we're proposing is that this cell geometry framework could be a simple

722
00:44:07.158 --> 00:44:09.568
way to monitor cancer cell plasticity.

723
00:44:10.028 --> 00:44:14.008
Indeed, the ability of cells to travel within this two-dimensional space

724
00:44:14.588 --> 00:44:17.688
is a good proxy or good readout of cancer cell plasticity.

725
00:44:19.268 --> 00:44:23.048
So now that we can use this very simple method to monitor and to quantify

726
00:44:23.148 --> 00:44:26.568
cell plasticity, the next question is, can we actually control

727
00:44:26.588 --> 00:44:27.228
plasticity?

728
00:44:29.528 --> 00:44:32.347
This, of course, therapeutically, it would be far more interesting.

729
00:44:33.508 --> 00:44:37.288
So instead of using drugs such as the standard of care treatment, the BRAF/MEK

730
00:44:37.328 --> 00:44:39.728
inhibitors, that promotes divergent

731
00:44:40.628 --> 00:44:43.208
persistent trajectories, we thought that

732
00:44:44.328 --> 00:44:48.048
identifying drugs or combination of drugs that promote a

733
00:44:48.168 --> 00:44:52.148
uniform and predictable trajectory would be quite

734
00:44:52.428 --> 00:44:56.168
exciting and would, of course, dramatically help the

735
00:44:56.228 --> 00:44:57.148
development of

736
00:44:58.488 --> 00:45:01.688
rational combination strategies.

737
00:45:03.868 --> 00:45:07.668
So we searched for a number of combinations that would

738
00:45:07.708 --> 00:45:11.568
promote uniform adaptation strategy, and what we found

739
00:45:11.608 --> 00:45:15.118
is this TP, this combination,

740
00:45:15.648 --> 00:45:19.098
trametinib, palbociclib, so a MEK inhibitor and

741
00:45:19.208 --> 00:45:22.568
CDK4/CDK6 inhibitor, promote indeed this

742
00:45:22.768 --> 00:45:24.728
uniform type of adaptive mechanism.

743
00:45:25.628 --> 00:45:29.288
Here you can see cells from 20 different cell

744
00:45:29.328 --> 00:45:33.318
lines, spanning again a wide range of genotypes and phenotypes adapting

745
00:45:33.468 --> 00:45:36.648
to the trametinib/palbociclib combination.

746
00:45:36.928 --> 00:45:40.368
You see that the cells move along this mel to mes

747
00:45:40.428 --> 00:45:42.988
trajectory and tend to increase the cell volume.

748
00:45:44.588 --> 00:45:48.288
So we were quite excited and surprised by the fact

749
00:45:48.428 --> 00:45:51.908
that this combination is able to induce a uniform

750
00:45:52.068 --> 00:45:55.868
adaptive response irrespective of the genotype and the phenotype of the cells.

751
00:45:56.388 --> 00:46:00.268
And again, we were quite excited about this because therapeutically, this could be

752
00:46:00.328 --> 00:46:00.968
exploited.

753
00:46:01.868 --> 00:46:05.788
So we searched a number of ways through which we could target these cells

754
00:46:05.868 --> 00:46:09.448
that increase the cell volume, so the persistent cells with the high volume,

755
00:46:10.608 --> 00:46:14.568
and realized using transcriptomic methods that these cells exhibit

756
00:46:14.608 --> 00:46:15.668
features of

757
00:46:17.228 --> 00:46:19.348
autophagy and

