01:01:14.944 --> 01:01:18.344
fast are they growing? But today, I'd also like to argue that it can tell us

1010
01:01:18.384 --> 01:01:20.184
something about the phenotypic evolution.

1011
01:01:20.204 --> 01:01:21.914
And to explain what I mean,

1012
01:01:24.024 --> 01:01:27.684
consider cell states like we heard today from the previous speakers, but

1013
01:01:27.764 --> 01:01:31.504
also epithelial-mesenchymal transitions or cancer stemness,

1014
01:01:32.084 --> 01:01:36.044
and the fundamental question of whether those cell states are actually heritable.

1015
01:01:36.184 --> 01:01:39.994
Can they be propagated across cell division from parent to progeny?

1016
01:01:40.724 --> 01:01:44.004
And this phylogenetic tree can help answer that question.

1017
01:01:44.484 --> 01:01:48.344
So if we can generate a high-resolution phylogenetic tree directly from a

1018
01:01:48.364 --> 01:01:52.304
patient sample, and can annotate the terminal nodes or the leaves of the

1019
01:01:52.364 --> 01:01:55.684
tree with this phenotypic cell state, we can distinguish

1020
01:01:55.724 --> 01:01:59.684
between scenarios like this tree on the left-hand side, where

1021
01:01:59.724 --> 01:02:01.124
you can see that it's very structural.

1022
01:02:01.164 --> 01:02:04.764
That's how a heritable tree looks like versus this, where

1023
01:02:05.024 --> 01:02:07.764
the phenotype is distributed much more randomly.

1024
01:02:08.824 --> 01:02:11.864
Josh Schiffman in the lab developed a quantitative

1025
01:02:12.484 --> 01:02:15.374
framework, a phylodynamic framework that allows us to measure this.

1026
01:02:15.984 --> 01:02:19.664
So we use Moran's I, a metric of phylogenetic

1027
01:02:19.724 --> 01:02:23.684
autocorrelation. What it basically asks is, if I have two cells that are

1028
01:02:23.764 --> 01:02:27.664
found together on the tree, closely on the tree, and I'm looking at a particular

1029
01:02:27.684 --> 01:02:30.024
phenotype, will that phenotype match up?

1030
01:02:30.064 --> 01:02:33.804
And the idea is that if it's heritable, neighboring cells on the tree

1031
01:02:34.164 --> 01:02:37.884
should share this phenotype. But it also offer a

1032
01:02:37.904 --> 01:02:41.714
potential novel and quantitative measurable definition of cancer cell

1033
01:02:41.784 --> 01:02:45.624
plasticity. It's one minus heritability. It's the complement of heritability.

1034
01:02:45.644 --> 01:02:49.524
If a cell has to have the same phenotype as its parent, then there's no

1035
01:02:49.924 --> 01:02:51.584
freedom of will. There's no plasticity.

1036
01:02:51.624 --> 01:02:55.314
If a cell can toggle between those cell state, then there's high degree of

1037
01:02:55.344 --> 01:02:55.964
plasticity.

1038
01:02:57.264 --> 01:03:00.884
So how do we generate those high-resolution phylogenetic tree directly from patient

1039
01:03:00.944 --> 01:03:04.694
samples? In model organism, we have all these advanced tools,

1040
01:03:04.964 --> 01:03:07.504
CRISPR screening tools to generate high-resolution trees.

1041
01:03:07.884 --> 01:03:10.504
But in patients, we have to rely on retrospective

1042
01:03:11.364 --> 01:03:13.603
lineage reconstruction. We have to use native marks.

1043
01:03:14.034 --> 01:03:17.824
And Fede Gaite, who's now faculty at Princess Margaret, Renaud Chanier, who's at

1044
01:03:17.904 --> 01:03:18.344
MSK,

1045
01:03:19.404 --> 01:03:22.914
a few years back, noticed that when we collect single-cell methylomes,

1046
01:03:23.384 --> 01:03:27.124
we are able to capture what we call epimutations, stochastic

1047
01:03:27.164 --> 01:03:31.134
changes to DNA methylation that are just happening as errors when

1048
01:03:31.164 --> 01:03:31.524
the cell

1049
01:03:32.744 --> 01:03:36.204
genome is copied and are yet heritable and can be

1050
01:03:36.304 --> 01:03:38.364
used to reconstruct phylogenies.

1051
01:03:39.104 --> 01:03:42.684
So with this approach, together with Marjo Suva, we

1052
01:03:42.964 --> 01:03:46.944
profiled glioblastoma cells. And I'm showing here one example where we can use

1053
01:03:46.984 --> 01:03:50.764
the methylation data to reconstruct the phylogenetic tree

1054
01:03:50.804 --> 01:03:54.264
directly from a primary patient sample. This is a single time point sample.

1055
01:03:54.684 --> 01:03:58.324
And because we work with the single-cell multi-omics, we also have RNA from the

1056
01:03:58.384 --> 01:04:02.074
same cell, and we can annotate the different cell state that Marjo and

1057
01:04:02.164 --> 01:04:05.324
colleagues have described are so important to biology of disease.

1058
01:04:05.424 --> 01:04:08.664
Stem-like cell state, astrocytic, mesenchymal, and so forth.

1059
01:04:08.724 --> 01:04:12.564
And we show that they are actually heritable, meaning that they are propagated

1060
01:04:12.604 --> 01:04:16.104
from parent to progeny across cell division.

1061
01:04:16.113 --> 01:04:19.404
Now we can take this a step further, and instead of looking at what we call

1062
01:04:19.464 --> 01:04:23.314
phylogenetic autocorrelation, whether that phenotype is found on neighboring

1063
01:04:23.364 --> 01:04:27.304
cells of the tree, we can look at the relationship between two cell states.

1064
01:04:27.344 --> 01:04:31.113
Would those two cell state actually be neighboring on the tree as well,

1065
01:04:31.434 --> 01:04:34.494
suggesting that they have high degree of transition?

1066
01:04:35.264 --> 01:04:39.084
And when we do this analysis, we can, from a single time point sample,

1067
01:04:39.624 --> 01:04:42.944
estimate what are the transition probability between cell states.

1068
01:04:43.784 --> 01:04:47.594
And here we see that to move from a stem-like cell state into mesenchymal,

1069
01:04:48.044 --> 01:04:51.744
there is a necessary intermediary, which is the astrocytic cell state.

1070
01:04:53.004 --> 01:04:56.784
Further, we can interrogate differentiation

1071
01:04:56.864 --> 01:05:00.364
hierarchy. For example, we find that in IDH-mutant

1072
01:05:00.444 --> 01:05:04.144
gliomas, the differentiation hierarchy is largely preserved as

1073
01:05:04.204 --> 01:05:07.024
unidirectional, moving from stem to mature.

1074
01:05:07.484 --> 01:05:11.424
But in IDH wild-type glioblastoma, the differentiation hierarchy is

1075
01:05:11.484 --> 01:05:14.664
corrupted. It's bidirectional. There's also dedifferentiation.

1076
01:05:14.724 --> 01:05:18.583
Some of the stem cells that we're seeing are originating from mature cell that are

1077
01:05:18.624 --> 01:05:22.564
dedifferentiating. And that's important because there's a paradigm in glioma that

1078
01:05:22.574 --> 01:05:24.523
argues that we should target those stem cells.

1079
01:05:25.084 --> 01:05:28.914
But if mature cells can replenish the rank, that of course changes

1080
01:05:28.944 --> 01:05:31.104
how we should consider this.

1081
01:05:32.584 --> 01:05:36.384
Now, recently, work by Jyoti Nangalia and Peter Campbell at the Sanger and

1082
01:05:36.444 --> 01:05:37.464
others have

1083
01:05:38.944 --> 01:05:42.804
shown that in blood, we can collect hematopoietic stem cells,

1084
01:05:43.444 --> 01:05:47.404
grow them ex vivo in culture, and then submit them to whole genome sequencing,

1085
01:05:47.444 --> 01:05:51.344
and then use all the mutations that are found in the genome to reconstruct

1086
01:05:51.354 --> 01:05:55.304
the phylogenetic tree. And notably, this is a phylogenetic tree that can look

1087
01:05:55.404 --> 01:05:58.984
further into the past, all the way to the moment of conception.

1088
01:05:59.014 --> 01:06:02.884
And in this fascinating example, they showed that a tumor that was a

1089
01:06:03.164 --> 01:06:07.154
blood cancer, that was diagnosed at adulthood, actually originated from

1090
01:06:07.154 --> 01:06:09.844
a mutation that likely occurred in utero.

1091
01:06:09.854 --> 01:06:12.434
This is super exciting, but there are limitations.

1092
01:06:13.604 --> 01:06:16.764
You have to have live cells. They have to be culturable ex vivo,

1093
01:06:17.384 --> 01:06:21.274
and you're limited in probing the phenotype because, by

1094
01:06:21.304 --> 01:06:22.284
virtue of culturing them

1095
01:06:24.164 --> 01:06:27.324
in vitro, you are obviously disrupting the phenotype.

1096
01:06:27.804 --> 01:06:31.684
Single-cell whole-genome amplification could be an alternative route, but

1097
01:06:31.784 --> 01:06:35.504
up until very recently, the quality of the data was just not sufficient

1098
01:06:35.544 --> 01:06:39.024
to generate these phylogenies, and that has been recently

1099
01:06:39.124 --> 01:06:42.884
solved through a protocol that was developed by Chakra

1100
01:06:42.904 --> 01:06:46.724
Wad called primary template amplification that is really a massive step

1101
01:06:46.784 --> 01:06:49.104
forward in the quality of whole genome.

1102
01:06:49.144 --> 01:06:53.104
However, there are issues with scalability.

1103
01:06:53.224 --> 01:06:56.764
The cost, the labor, the time that's associated with producing this data

1104
01:06:57.304 --> 01:07:01.004
means that most of the published datasets that are out there involve only

1105
01:07:01.024 --> 01:07:04.780
dozens of cells.Just to give you one flavor, to generate

1106
01:07:04.940 --> 01:07:07.840
1,000 single-cell whole genomes, we need

1107
01:07:08.200 --> 01:07:12.000
35,000 pipette tips. And there's a team in the lab that came up with a

1108
01:07:12.040 --> 01:07:16.010
way to address all of the different cost and labor and time component, such that

1109
01:07:16.040 --> 01:07:18.500
we can really turn it into something that's more scalable.

1110
01:07:18.880 --> 01:07:20.510
We call this smart PTA.

1111
01:07:22.060 --> 01:07:25.560
Using this approach, we generated 3,500

1112
01:07:26.420 --> 01:07:30.000
matched whole genome and transcriptome from phenotypically normal

1113
01:07:30.040 --> 01:07:34.000
esophagus. This is the tissue that was shown by the Sanger colleague to

1114
01:07:34.080 --> 01:07:38.060
be completely replaced, carpeted with clones as we age,

1115
01:07:38.100 --> 01:07:42.000
clones bearing mutations in driver genes such as Notch1 and TP53.

1116
01:07:43.160 --> 01:07:47.120
And with this data, we can then retrace the evolution of those

1117
01:07:47.180 --> 01:07:51.090
cells. So we have cells that we collect from a 75-year-old, and

1118
01:07:51.120 --> 01:07:54.450
then we can trace their evolution all the way to the moment of conception.

1119
01:07:55.100 --> 01:07:58.900
And we can understand how different clones arose, when they

1120
01:07:58.910 --> 01:08:02.860
arose, and also what are the pattern of growth and can show you an example from

1121
01:08:02.870 --> 01:08:06.630
a clone here that grew stably over time versus another

1122
01:08:06.660 --> 01:08:10.340
clone where you see that there is an inflection point matching with a

1123
01:08:10.860 --> 01:08:14.300
massive increase in proliferation rate, which coincides with the

1124
01:08:14.340 --> 01:08:16.080
acquisition of a driver mutation.

1125
01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:21.540
In another example, we can look at TP53 mutated clones, and we find that

1126
01:08:21.580 --> 01:08:24.940
in phenotypically normal tissue, there's nothing wrong with this tissue under the

1127
01:08:24.980 --> 01:08:28.700
microscope, we find TP53 clones. And not only that, some of them have

1128
01:08:28.900 --> 01:08:30.721
complete biallelic inactivation.

1129
01:08:31.061 --> 01:08:34.300
And yet, based on the phylogenetic reconstruction, we know that they are

1130
01:08:35.940 --> 01:08:37.840
in the tissue for 10, 15 years,

1131
01:08:38.800 --> 01:08:42.221
and that really challenges us to think again about what is that

1132
01:08:42.540 --> 01:08:46.460
elusive cancer Rubicon that separates the non-transformed

1133
01:08:46.521 --> 01:08:47.900
from a transformed cell.

1134
01:08:49.460 --> 01:08:53.240
Back to the glioma example, again, in collaboration with Mario Suva's lab,

1135
01:08:53.601 --> 01:08:56.940
we collected 2,500 single cell with whole genome and

1136
01:08:56.960 --> 01:08:57.670
transcriptome.

1137
01:08:58.681 --> 01:09:02.420
And here you can see that we can reconstruct the phylogeny of those cells

1138
01:09:02.440 --> 01:09:05.980
from the moment of origination and again, ask the

1139
01:09:06.040 --> 01:09:08.800
fundamental question of are those cell states heritable?

1140
01:09:09.181 --> 01:09:12.559
Now we have a positive control that's a genetic lesion, obviously

1141
01:09:12.860 --> 01:09:16.580
highly heritable. We have a negative control sequencing depth that's just

1142
01:09:16.660 --> 01:09:19.320
a technical feature. And all of those

1143
01:09:20.240 --> 01:09:24.010
features in between are those cell states, stem-like cell state, mesenchymal,

1144
01:09:24.300 --> 01:09:27.300
that again are showing a marker of heritability.

1145
01:09:28.760 --> 01:09:32.101
As I mentioned, we can also estimate transition probability and again validate

1146
01:09:32.561 --> 01:09:36.141
between stem and mesenchymal. We have to go through an astrocytic cell state.

1147
01:09:36.181 --> 01:09:39.780
And again, this is from a single time point primary patient

1148
01:09:39.840 --> 01:09:43.380
sample. But when we look at different tumor regions, we see

1149
01:09:43.420 --> 01:09:47.360
differences. In peritumoral areas, we see a push towards dedifferentiation,

1150
01:09:47.440 --> 01:09:50.221
towards more stem-like cell state that's consistent with those cells

1151
01:09:51.940 --> 01:09:53.061
enabling the

1152
01:09:53.900 --> 01:09:56.620
invasion of glioma into normal brain parenchyma.

1153
01:09:57.060 --> 01:10:01.000
In necrotic core, we see a push towards more mature cell state, likely

1154
01:10:01.020 --> 01:10:04.760
reflecting the intense infiltration by tumor microenvironment and myeloid

1155
01:10:04.800 --> 01:10:05.100
cells.

1156
01:10:07.220 --> 01:10:11.200
Because we have single-cell whole genomes, we can also study a feature

1157
01:10:11.280 --> 01:10:15.180
of glioma, a very interesting feature of glioma, extra chromosomal

1158
01:10:15.220 --> 01:10:18.920
DNA, and we can solve the breakpoints of the amplicon and the copy

1159
01:10:18.980 --> 01:10:22.580
number at the single-cell level and identify the remarkable

1160
01:10:22.620 --> 01:10:23.700
ability of those

1161
01:10:24.520 --> 01:10:26.300
extra chromosomal fragments to evolve.

1162
01:10:26.720 --> 01:10:30.520
Within just a few hundred samples, we discovered more than 12 different

1163
01:10:30.680 --> 01:10:34.420
version of EGFR extra chromosomal DNA, ecDNA,

1164
01:10:34.940 --> 01:10:38.640
that all started from the same amplicon and then are continuously

1165
01:10:38.740 --> 01:10:41.210
sculpted and remodeled as the tumor evolved.

1166
01:10:42.040 --> 01:10:43.600
There's another feature that's, I think,

1167
01:10:44.900 --> 01:10:48.540
surprising and fascinating, and I'm just simplifying here.

1168
01:10:48.790 --> 01:10:50.600
There are two versions of this ecDNA.

1169
01:10:50.660 --> 01:10:54.420
There's a six mega base version and then a derivative of that of a one mega

1170
01:10:54.480 --> 01:10:57.980
base version. And you can see that although they segregate by the different

1171
01:10:58.060 --> 01:11:01.720
clades, there are also instances where even neighboring

1172
01:11:01.730 --> 01:11:05.540
cells in a phylogeny have different versions of this ecDNA.

1173
01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:09.450
Sometimes both are found within the same cell, again, testifying to

1174
01:11:09.540 --> 01:11:13.320
how the inheritance is unexpected and does not

1175
01:11:13.360 --> 01:11:14.620
follow a Mendelian pattern.

1176
01:11:16.040 --> 01:11:19.720
And lastly, we can also ask questions about migration.

1177
01:11:20.220 --> 01:11:22.600
How do cells move from one place to the other?

1178
01:11:23.560 --> 01:11:27.300
And in fact, these frameworks draw on frameworks that use

1179
01:11:27.340 --> 01:11:31.300
phylogenetics, for example, to estimate patterns of migrations in early human

1180
01:11:31.320 --> 01:11:34.600
history. We can identify which areas of the

1181
01:11:34.680 --> 01:11:38.500
tree show higher degrees of mixing that likely move

1182
01:11:38.580 --> 01:11:42.110
around and then correlate it with the phenotype when we observe that the

1183
01:11:42.120 --> 01:11:46.100
phenotype seem to converge towards a stem-like cell state, again,

1184
01:11:46.480 --> 01:11:50.020
testifying to the ability of those cells to infiltrate the normal parenchyma

1185
01:11:50.500 --> 01:11:52.100
as well as an invasion signature.

1186
01:11:53.200 --> 01:11:56.670
So just to summarize this first part, I'm excited about this

1187
01:11:57.160 --> 01:12:00.960
new way of studying this problem, this

1188
01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:04.780
high-resolution phylogenetic tree that in addition has the ability to

1189
01:12:04.840 --> 01:12:07.980
annotate the terminal nodes or the leaves with phenotypes.

1190
01:12:09.180 --> 01:12:12.550
This allows us to ask really fundamental question about heritability,

1191
01:12:12.630 --> 01:12:15.760
plasticity, as well as measure cell state transition

1192
01:12:15.840 --> 01:12:19.000
in humans, in a primary patient sample.

1193
01:12:19.040 --> 01:12:22.940
And we hope to build new technologies that could scale this up to hundreds of

1194
01:12:22.980 --> 01:12:24.600
thousands of cells and millions of cells.

1195
01:12:24.680 --> 01:12:28.560
But there is another factor that I think is interesting to point out.

1196
01:12:29.500 --> 01:12:32.240
When we think about inheritance, we think about memory.

1197
01:12:32.470 --> 01:12:36.150
It's a common experience in oncology that each

1198
01:12:36.180 --> 01:12:39.180
cycle of therapy results in shorter and shorter remissions.

1199
01:12:39.220 --> 01:12:42.410
Something is being remembered and propagated across cell

1200
01:12:42.460 --> 01:12:45.800
division to new generations of cancer cells.

1201
01:12:46.200 --> 01:12:49.800
And we can ask the question with these trees, what is the mode of

1202
01:12:49.820 --> 01:12:52.960
propagation? How is the information inherited?

1203
01:12:53.060 --> 01:12:56.340
How is it passed along? Is it through genetic features like

1204
01:12:56.380 --> 01:12:59.540
ecDNA? Is it through epigenetic features?

1205
01:12:59.580 --> 01:13:01.980
Is it through tumor microenvironmental interactions?

1206
01:13:02.350 --> 01:13:05.960
And the idea is that we can decorate the same trees with all of these potential

1207
01:13:06.020 --> 01:13:09.920
explanatory features and through this cross-correlation explain how much

1208
01:13:09.960 --> 01:13:13.500
of the heritability is driven by each one of those factors.

1209
01:13:14.600 --> 01:13:18.540
Now, switching to the second part of the talk, using the genome as a residual

1210
01:13:18.600 --> 01:13:19.880
disease sensor, and

1211
01:13:20.760 --> 01:13:24.720
MaxIntroduced us to this problem, but just

1212
01:13:24.750 --> 01:13:28.660
to reiterate how unusual it is in what we do in oncology compared to

1213
01:13:28.730 --> 01:13:32.410
other areas of medicine. So take the example of adjuvant chemotherapy,

1214
01:13:32.770 --> 01:13:34.410
and this is a real example we can take.

1215
01:13:35.610 --> 01:13:39.330
We treat often 100 patients to benefit three

1216
01:13:39.510 --> 01:13:43.210
or four or five. There are many patients who actually

1217
01:13:43.470 --> 01:13:47.410
were cured by surgery, and yet we're treating them with probably the worst thing

1218
01:13:47.450 --> 01:13:50.449
that a doctor can give a patient in terms of cost and toxicity.

1219
01:13:51.010 --> 01:13:54.370
And there are other patients that have residual disease, that have

1220
01:13:54.610 --> 01:13:58.530
potential lethal disease, and do not benefit from this costly and

1221
01:13:58.590 --> 01:14:01.930
toxic therapy, and potentially need urgently something else.

1222
01:14:02.340 --> 01:14:06.070
And this is true in the adjuvant setting, but it's also true more broadly

1223
01:14:06.210 --> 01:14:08.919
across the continuum of clinical cancer

1224
01:14:09.030 --> 01:14:12.930
care. And we started working on this problem 10 years when I

1225
01:14:12.950 --> 01:14:14.120
started the lab in New York City.

1226
01:14:15.230 --> 01:14:19.000
We were excited about circulating tumor DNA, this idea that you have

1227
01:14:19.230 --> 01:14:22.670
DNA in the blood that can be used to identify residual disease.

1228
01:14:22.710 --> 01:14:26.570
And the paradigm then, and potentially still mostly now in industry and

1229
01:14:26.610 --> 01:14:29.210
academia, was to do deep targeted sequencing.

1230
01:14:29.270 --> 01:14:33.170
The idea is that circulating tumor DNA in the plasma is very sparse,

1231
01:14:33.570 --> 01:14:37.250
so we need to sequence at informative loci, let's say the KRAS locus,

1232
01:14:37.750 --> 01:14:41.520
very, very deeply, such that we can capture, let's say, one fragment

1233
01:14:41.530 --> 01:14:42.300
out of a million.

1234
01:14:43.770 --> 01:14:45.410
Now, we realized as we started to

1235
01:14:46.650 --> 01:14:49.750
look at these data, that there was an elephant in the room that wasn't as

1236
01:14:49.810 --> 01:14:53.770
recognized then, but I think is much more recognized today, that

1237
01:14:53.810 --> 01:14:57.510
when we draw a tube of blood from a patient, there's only so much

1238
01:14:57.550 --> 01:15:01.130
DNA in it. And in fact, there are only a few thousand genomic

1239
01:15:01.170 --> 01:15:05.070
equivalents. So in theory, we can sequence a million X that

1240
01:15:05.250 --> 01:15:09.120
KRAS locus, but in practice, we're hitting our head against the ceiling, the

1241
01:15:09.250 --> 01:15:11.330
number of actual physical fragments.

1242
01:15:11.990 --> 01:15:15.450
So then we thought, how can we overcome this limitation?

1243
01:15:15.490 --> 01:15:19.410
And we thought that breadth could potentially supplant depth.

1244
01:15:19.450 --> 01:15:23.090
Instead of doing target sequencing, we can aggregate signal

1245
01:15:23.150 --> 01:15:24.370
across the entire genome.

1246
01:15:25.870 --> 01:15:29.780
So statistically speaking, looking at one spot in the genome 10,000

1247
01:15:29.780 --> 01:15:33.729
times should be equivalent to looking across 10,000 spots in the genome

1248
01:15:33.830 --> 01:15:37.490
much more shallowly. But from the detection perspective,

1249
01:15:37.810 --> 01:15:40.590
this results in a radical, dramatic change.

1250
01:15:41.010 --> 01:15:44.870
Whereas with a single locus, let's say digital drop with PCR, where you

1251
01:15:44.930 --> 01:15:48.770
see a precipitous drop in sensitivity when we go below,

1252
01:15:49.090 --> 01:15:52.850
let's say 1 to 1,000. That's the ceiling that I was talking about, the number of

1253
01:15:52.870 --> 01:15:56.690
genomic equivalents. But when we are tracking 10,000 mutations across the

1254
01:15:56.730 --> 01:16:00.650
genome, even with a modest sequencing effort of 30 or 50x, we can

1255
01:16:00.870 --> 01:16:03.170
engage very much lower

1256
01:16:04.950 --> 01:16:06.930
concentration of ctDNA.

1257
01:16:08.530 --> 01:16:10.990
And moreover, we provide a quantitative metric.

1258
01:16:11.150 --> 01:16:15.110
Doctors, clinicians, patients need not only to know if there is residual

1259
01:16:15.130 --> 01:16:18.050
disease or not, but also is it coming up? Is it coming down?

1260
01:16:18.090 --> 01:16:20.400
We need a quantitative metric to help guide therapy.

1261
01:16:21.870 --> 01:16:25.370
So how can we do better? One thing we have done is to leverage

1262
01:16:25.380 --> 01:16:29.330
artificial intelligence to increase signal and decrease

1263
01:16:29.370 --> 01:16:33.330
noise. Remember, there are only a few somatic mutations because of the sparsity of

1264
01:16:33.350 --> 01:16:35.630
ctDNA, and they're

1265
01:16:36.990 --> 01:16:38.510
within a sea of

1266
01:16:39.590 --> 01:16:43.550
sequencing errors and other artifacts that are related to the damage to the actual

1267
01:16:43.570 --> 01:16:47.230
DNA molecules. And Adam Wittman, who's currently faculty at MSK,

1268
01:16:47.730 --> 01:16:51.199
tackled this by understanding that there are lots of different features that

1269
01:16:51.230 --> 01:16:54.150
distinguish true somatic mutations from

1270
01:16:55.450 --> 01:16:59.290
sequencing artifact and damage to the DNA, the particular

1271
01:16:59.330 --> 01:17:03.190
mutational signature, where in the genome, the fragment length, and so on,

1272
01:17:03.610 --> 01:17:07.170
and they could be best integrated using modern deep learning

1273
01:17:07.250 --> 01:17:11.210
architectures. Now, one feature that's important to remember

1274
01:17:11.270 --> 01:17:14.750
is that these deep learning architectures are very data hungry.

1275
01:17:14.770 --> 01:17:18.630
They need training sets that involve lots and lots of observation.

1276
01:17:18.650 --> 01:17:22.050
And this can be done because our classifier is classifying

1277
01:17:22.110 --> 01:17:25.360
mutations at the level of the individual DNA fragment.

1278
01:17:25.730 --> 01:17:29.680
It goes fragment by fragment and asks the question: Is the variant we're

1279
01:17:29.710 --> 01:17:33.170
seeing an actual somatic mutation, or is it some kind of

1280
01:17:33.180 --> 01:17:34.210
artifact or error?

1281
01:17:35.690 --> 01:17:37.430
So we validated this together with

1282
01:17:38.610 --> 01:17:42.470
Claus Andersen from Aarhus. This is with digital drop of PCR,

1283
01:17:42.540 --> 01:17:44.270
and we have similar results with Signatera.

1284
01:17:44.739 --> 01:17:48.680
And what you can see is above 1 to 1,000, 1 to 10,000,

1285
01:17:48.750 --> 01:17:52.240
there is a good matchup between our results and the targeted approach.

1286
01:17:52.590 --> 01:17:56.510
But as we go below that level, the targeted approaches start to

1287
01:17:56.590 --> 01:17:59.290
struggle, again, because of that limitation

1288
01:17:59.350 --> 01:18:02.520
on the number of genomic equivalents.

1289
01:18:03.570 --> 01:18:07.470
What it allows us to do is to measure circulating tumor DNA at

1290
01:18:07.570 --> 01:18:10.610
landmark time points after surgery or after adjuvant

1291
01:18:10.690 --> 01:18:14.570
chemotherapy and predict outcome even more than two years

1292
01:18:14.610 --> 01:18:15.650
before it occurs.

1293
01:18:16.890 --> 01:18:20.250
Now, I mentioned how we can use artificial intelligence to

1294
01:18:21.550 --> 01:18:24.970
increase signal and decrease noise, but we can also use

1295
01:18:25.050 --> 01:18:27.110
molecular ways to do so.

1296
01:18:28.250 --> 01:18:32.050
So one of the things that happened in the last couple of years was a seismic shift

1297
01:18:32.130 --> 01:18:35.910
in the sequencing market. For many years, the cost of sequencing has

1298
01:18:36.050 --> 01:18:36.630
stagnated,

1299
01:18:37.450 --> 01:18:41.010
largely from commercial reasons, but in the last couple of years, we've seen a

1300
01:18:41.150 --> 01:18:43.990
massive drop in the cost, almost an order of magnitude.

1301
01:18:45.370 --> 01:18:49.180
Alex Zhang, who's now faculty in Montreal, reasons that we can

1302
01:18:49.270 --> 01:18:51.710
use this extra capacity to

1303
01:18:52.630 --> 01:18:54.790
perform what's called duplex sequencing.

1304
01:18:54.890 --> 01:18:58.150
So in duplex sequencing, those errors that are caused by DNA

1305
01:18:58.250 --> 01:19:01.630
damage can be distinguished from true somatic mutations

1306
01:19:02.010 --> 01:19:04.510
because they're not found on the complementary strand.

1307
01:19:04.570 --> 01:19:08.330
We barcode each one of the strands and sequence them

1308
01:19:08.430 --> 01:19:12.250
separately, but through finding complementary strands, we

1309
01:19:12.290 --> 01:19:16.130
can ask, is it a true somatic mutation, meaning the bases on both

1310
01:19:16.210 --> 01:19:19.970
strands are complementary, or is it some kind of damage to the DNA

1311
01:19:20.330 --> 01:19:24.230
where we would find that they're non-complementary?What this allows us to do is to

1312
01:19:24.270 --> 01:19:26.730
really get very clean mutational profiles.

1313
01:19:27.050 --> 01:19:30.770
This is how a melanoma tumor looks like with a strong UV

1314
01:19:31.430 --> 01:19:35.090
signature. This is how the whole genome looks like without this duplex.

1315
01:19:35.250 --> 01:19:37.550
You see that there's very little similarity.

1316
01:19:37.590 --> 01:19:41.550
That's because most of the variants we're seeing are all sorts

1317
01:19:41.590 --> 01:19:45.250
of artifacts and errors. But when we apply the duplex

1318
01:19:45.270 --> 01:19:49.130
correction, you see that it becomes almost a perfect mirror of what we

1319
01:19:49.150 --> 01:19:52.810
expect, suggesting that now most of the mutations are actually

1320
01:19:53.130 --> 01:19:55.030
true somatic variants.

1321
01:19:56.630 --> 01:20:00.390
Now, one of the challenges of duplex sequencing is that it's very sequencing

1322
01:20:00.770 --> 01:20:01.230
greedy.

1323
01:20:02.150 --> 01:20:06.000
We need to sequence 100X, and we get at the end of the day,

1324
01:20:06.090 --> 01:20:09.950
maybe one or two X. And that's because what we do is we barcode

1325
01:20:10.010 --> 01:20:13.690
both of the strands, but then denature the DNA molecule, put them in a

1326
01:20:13.850 --> 01:20:17.440
big pool with billions of different fragments, and then hope that

1327
01:20:17.590 --> 01:20:21.290
after the sequencing procedure, we can pair them back together.

1328
01:20:22.630 --> 01:20:26.430
So together with colleagues at Ultima, we came up with a different

1329
01:20:26.470 --> 01:20:30.190
solution, and that leverages the Ultima sequencer ability to

1330
01:20:32.630 --> 01:20:35.850
sequence each individual fragment on an emulsion bead.

1331
01:20:36.450 --> 01:20:40.430
What it allows you to do is to load onto the sequencer directly

1332
01:20:40.450 --> 01:20:44.180
a double-stranded molecule, so that instead of relying on

1333
01:20:44.210 --> 01:20:47.730
catching them back after the sequencing, they stick

1334
01:20:47.750 --> 01:20:49.880
together throughout the sequencing procedure.

1335
01:20:50.450 --> 01:20:54.110
So we could get accuracy that's very similar to duplex,

1336
01:20:54.550 --> 01:20:57.250
but more than an order of magnitude higher efficiency.

1337
01:20:57.290 --> 01:21:01.190
What it means is that essentially you can do a regular, cheap whole

1338
01:21:01.270 --> 01:21:04.850
genome sequencing and have a quality of a duplex

1339
01:21:05.330 --> 01:21:05.730
genome.

1340
01:21:07.090 --> 01:21:10.890
So how does it work? In the tumor-informed setting, we identify all the somatic

1341
01:21:10.950 --> 01:21:14.910
mutations that are found in the tumor and then use it as a fingerprint and try

1342
01:21:14.930 --> 01:21:16.810
to detect those mutations in the plasma.

1343
01:21:16.840 --> 01:21:20.750
And you can see here in lung cancer that we are able, just with

1344
01:21:20.770 --> 01:21:22.810
a 30X whole genome, to

1345
01:21:24.010 --> 01:21:26.390
have sensitivity in the parts per million range.

1346
01:21:26.810 --> 01:21:30.450
We also thought, "What happens a few years from now when sequencing cost

1347
01:21:30.890 --> 01:21:34.550
drops even further?" We can sequence a 300X, and we can go to

1348
01:21:34.590 --> 01:21:38.430
below the parts per million range, which I think is very exciting.

1349
01:21:39.470 --> 01:21:43.310
Jonathan Duan from Charlie Swanton's group validated it on the TRACERx

1350
01:21:43.320 --> 01:21:46.750
cohort, and we compared it to Personalis, which is perhaps

1351
01:21:46.810 --> 01:21:48.470
the most advanced

1352
01:21:51.410 --> 01:21:55.300
patient-specific targeted panel using 800 SNVs and

1353
01:21:55.390 --> 01:21:57.690
a personalized hybrid capture panel.

1354
01:21:58.370 --> 01:22:02.310
And you can see that the performance is largely similar, as

1355
01:22:02.350 --> 01:22:04.530
is the ability to predict the future outcome.

1356
01:22:06.730 --> 01:22:10.550
Because the profiles are so clean, because the mutations are so

1357
01:22:10.610 --> 01:22:14.430
distinct now, we can again try to see if we can just

1358
01:22:14.530 --> 01:22:18.490
use the plasma to try and find the mutational signature of the tumor.

1359
01:22:19.030 --> 01:22:22.870
And this was done with Bishoy Faltas from Cornell, and we looked for the APOBEC

1360
01:22:22.950 --> 01:22:26.550
signature that we heard today that is very frequently seen in bladder

1361
01:22:26.590 --> 01:22:30.520
cancer. And in fact, even if we don't have the matched tumor, which is

1362
01:22:30.530 --> 01:22:34.290
sometimes limiting in clinical scenarios, we can use the APOBEC

1363
01:22:34.350 --> 01:22:36.470
signature as our detection signal.

1364
01:22:37.710 --> 01:22:41.490
We did a similar exercise in lung cancer, this time

1365
01:22:41.550 --> 01:22:45.490
using the tobacco signature as a detection signal, again, in the absence

1366
01:22:45.690 --> 01:22:46.670
of a matched tumor.

1367
01:22:48.290 --> 01:22:49.650
So why is this so exciting?

1368
01:22:50.590 --> 01:22:54.510
Just to give you a clinical example. Here, this is from Adam's work.

1369
01:22:54.550 --> 01:22:55.150
You can see here

1370
01:22:56.250 --> 01:22:59.870
two patients that one of them had

1371
01:23:00.010 --> 01:23:03.740
a clear benefit from immunotherapy, this is a melanoma, and

1372
01:23:03.770 --> 01:23:05.730
another patient where there was limited benefit.

1373
01:23:05.760 --> 01:23:09.130
And we can tell this without imaging, even after three weeks.

1374
01:23:10.190 --> 01:23:13.610
But what we noticed is that there are some individuals that had a decrease in the

1375
01:23:13.650 --> 01:23:17.450
circulating tumor DNA early and yet had adverse

1376
01:23:17.570 --> 01:23:20.250
outcome, early recurrence, and we wondered why.

1377
01:23:20.280 --> 01:23:24.170
And we went back to the patient records, and we observed that those

1378
01:23:24.190 --> 01:23:27.890
patients that had a good response initially were

1379
01:23:27.950 --> 01:23:31.590
treated often with steroids. And we know that in immunotherapy, many

1380
01:23:31.630 --> 01:23:35.250
times there's immune-related adverse effects, and oncologists

1381
01:23:35.590 --> 01:23:39.110
give steroids to these patients to try and treat those immune effects.

1382
01:23:39.470 --> 01:23:43.080
But these steroids are reversing the course of the

1383
01:23:43.080 --> 01:23:46.650
disease, are reversing the therapeutic impact of immunotherapy.

1384
01:23:47.630 --> 01:23:51.570
And I think that this type of information given to clinicians and to patients

1385
01:23:51.610 --> 01:23:54.470
could help us all optimize how we treat patients.

1386
01:23:54.510 --> 01:23:57.810
In this example, I'm showing you how we're treating with a

1387
01:23:57.870 --> 01:24:01.550
T-cell-directed therapy but also provide steroids that are

1388
01:24:01.590 --> 01:24:03.610
eliminating those very same T cells.

1389
01:24:05.290 --> 01:24:08.930
So just to summarize, I'm really excited about turning the cancer

1390
01:24:08.970 --> 01:24:12.570
genome from a static descriptor into a dynamic clinical

1391
01:24:12.650 --> 01:24:13.110
sensor.

1392
01:24:14.370 --> 01:24:17.630
It has favorable cost and scalability for MRD.

1393
01:24:18.190 --> 01:24:21.430
The cost of a 30X whole genome today is just $80, and

1394
01:24:21.530 --> 01:24:24.550
scalability is because we don't need patient-specific

1395
01:24:25.130 --> 01:24:28.210
reagents. We don't need complex workflows, centralized lab.

1396
01:24:28.650 --> 01:24:30.810
Anyone can do this anywhere across the globe.

1397
01:24:31.110 --> 01:24:33.870
Whole genome sequencing is the easiest library to make.

1398
01:24:34.390 --> 01:24:36.660
There's opportunity to integrate additional features.

1399
01:24:36.690 --> 01:24:38.430
I didn't have time to go over it today,

1400
01:24:39.450 --> 01:24:42.710
but our work has shown that we can detect signals of aneuploidy, copy number

1401
01:24:42.770 --> 01:24:46.500
variation, fragmentomics, or changes in fragment length,

1402
01:24:47.090 --> 01:24:50.950
and epigenetic features. And whole genome sequencing in this era

1403
01:24:51.030 --> 01:24:54.810
of AI serves as a learning system. Every

1404
01:24:55.310 --> 01:24:59.210
whole genome that we sequence, we can learn and optimize the algorithms for the

1405
01:24:59.250 --> 01:25:03.150
next one, which we can't do with those patient-specific panels that although

1406
01:25:03.160 --> 01:25:06.370
are providing really useful information today, cannot be

1407
01:25:06.450 --> 01:25:09.670
reinterrogated in the future. And as I showed you, the use

1408
01:25:09.730 --> 01:25:13.170
of machine learning and this high data

1409
01:25:13.310 --> 01:25:17.210
intense work can also pave the path to

1410
01:25:17.630 --> 01:25:19.190
plasma-only detection as well.

1411
01:25:20.290 --> 01:25:22.510
So just to summarize, in closing,

1412
01:25:23.570 --> 01:25:25.890
I'm excited about harnessing the cancer genome

1413
01:25:27.030 --> 01:25:29.810
to expose the hidden lives of cancer cells.

1414
01:25:29.850 --> 01:25:33.634
And these seem like two different problems, butIn

1415
01:25:33.794 --> 01:25:36.034
some ways, they are a shared ambition.

1416
01:25:36.094 --> 01:25:39.214
In both of those scenarios, we are trying to

1417
01:25:39.594 --> 01:25:42.574
extract weak but structured information

1418
01:25:43.714 --> 01:25:47.634
from complex mixtures. In one hand, we're looking at the genome to

1419
01:25:47.714 --> 01:25:50.214
read the history of the tumor,

1420
01:25:51.074 --> 01:25:54.934
understand its genetic and phenotypic evolution, and in the

1421
01:25:55.014 --> 01:25:58.874
other, we're using the genome as a sensor to read out residual disease

1422
01:25:58.914 --> 01:26:00.334
and predict future outcome.

1423
01:26:01.194 --> 01:26:01.474
Thank you.

1424
01:26:10.414 --> 01:26:11.194
Thank you, Dr. Landau.

1425
01:26:12.694 --> 01:26:15.454
Our fourth speaker of the session is Dr.

1426
01:26:16.314 --> 01:26:20.294
Jeannie Tee. She is a professor at the Peter MacCallum Cancer Center

1427
01:26:20.714 --> 01:26:23.594
and also gets the prize for having come the longest way to be here today.

1428
01:26:24.274 --> 01:26:27.954
Her talk is titled "MRD Directed Treatment Strategies in

1429
01:26:28.034 --> 01:26:28.894
Colorectal Cancer."

1430
01:26:38.413 --> 01:26:39.174
Good afternoon.

1431
01:26:41.054 --> 01:26:45.034
Firstly, I want to thank the program committee and chairs for this

1432
01:26:45.154 --> 01:26:49.134
kind invitation to speak today. It is truly a privilege to

1433
01:26:49.174 --> 01:26:49.694
be here.

1434
01:26:50.614 --> 01:26:53.454
Now, we've heard three outstanding talks

1435
01:26:54.114 --> 01:26:57.854
about how cancer cells persist and

1436
01:26:57.994 --> 01:26:58.554
evolve.

1437
01:26:59.514 --> 01:27:03.074
As a clinician, I find what is most compelling about

1438
01:27:03.194 --> 01:27:06.594
MRD is where this biology is now

1439
01:27:06.634 --> 01:27:08.974
clinically actionable. So

1440
01:27:09.794 --> 01:27:13.754
the focus on my talk today will be on how MRDs

1441
01:27:13.774 --> 01:27:16.724
are already influencing clinical decision making,

1442
01:27:17.554 --> 01:27:21.334
and also how it's starting to reshape the way we design clinical

1443
01:27:21.394 --> 01:27:24.714
trials and think about regulatory endpoints.

1444
01:27:26.994 --> 01:27:28.114
Here are my disclosures.

1445
01:27:30.654 --> 01:27:31.454
To start with,

1446
01:27:32.834 --> 01:27:34.694
I want to describe a

1447
01:27:35.714 --> 01:27:36.974
simple observation.

1448
01:27:38.134 --> 01:27:41.754
That is that cure in solid tumor and colorectal

1449
01:27:41.814 --> 01:27:45.754
cancer is fundamentally a function of disease

1450
01:27:45.854 --> 01:27:46.214
burden.

1451
01:27:47.264 --> 01:27:50.854
And we've learned from adjuvant trial

1452
01:27:50.934 --> 01:27:54.394
data, the seminal work back in 1990s and

1453
01:27:54.514 --> 01:27:55.314
2004,

1454
01:27:56.394 --> 01:28:00.014
that about 30% of patients with

1455
01:28:00.074 --> 01:28:02.294
micrometastatic disease, is a patient who

1456
01:28:02.534 --> 01:28:05.974
supposedly had their tumor resected,

1457
01:28:06.034 --> 01:28:09.694
micrometastatic disease, are cured by systemic

1458
01:28:10.154 --> 01:28:11.054
chemotherapy.

1459
01:28:12.134 --> 01:28:16.054
Whilst when the disease burden is high and clinically

1460
01:28:16.094 --> 01:28:20.054
detectable in imaging, that cure rate collapse to near

1461
01:28:20.094 --> 01:28:20.474
zero.

1462
01:28:21.654 --> 01:28:25.594
And this phenomenon is not unique to colorectal cancer.

1463
01:28:25.634 --> 01:28:28.954
We see it as in other solid tumor types as well as

1464
01:28:28.994 --> 01:28:32.254
hematological condition, as well as using

1465
01:28:32.314 --> 01:28:34.594
immunotherapy and CAR T-cell therapy.

1466
01:28:35.414 --> 01:28:39.404
And we consistently see the outcomes are better when the

1467
01:28:39.414 --> 01:28:42.794
disease burden is low. So if we want to cure more

1468
01:28:42.854 --> 01:28:45.554
cancers, we need to treat early.

1469
01:28:47.914 --> 01:28:51.774
But why have we not made progress, particularly in colorectal

1470
01:28:51.874 --> 01:28:55.714
cancer, since oxaliplatin-based doublet chemotherapy became

1471
01:28:55.854 --> 01:28:59.374
standard of care over two decades ago?

1472
01:28:59.414 --> 01:29:03.294
We've had eight negative phase three trials, none of

1473
01:29:03.334 --> 01:29:07.034
which have improved upon FOLFOX or CAPOX

1474
01:29:07.054 --> 01:29:07.934
chemotherapy.

1475
01:29:09.014 --> 01:29:12.934
And more recently, we have some promising signal from a

1476
01:29:12.994 --> 01:29:16.494
very biomarker-selected group of patients, but

1477
01:29:16.534 --> 01:29:19.374
overall, the gain has still been very modest.

1478
01:29:20.394 --> 01:29:24.214
So in my mind, I would argue that there are three key challenges that

1479
01:29:24.254 --> 01:29:25.294
have held us back.

1480
01:29:26.114 --> 01:29:29.974
The first is suboptimal patient selection, because most of the

1481
01:29:30.014 --> 01:29:33.534
patients we treat in the adjuvant setting don't actually have residual

